plete Series'' || 1-3 || 39 || [[Beyond International|Beyond Home Entertainment]] || Australia || February 5, 2012 || Whole series\n|-\n| colspan=7|The entire series is included.\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"background:#1E90FF|\n|}\n\n==Other media==\nJenny was featured as a playable character in the [[PlayStation 2]]/[[Wii]] and [[Nintendo DS]] versions of [[Nicktoons: Attack of the Toybots|''Nicktoons: Attack of the Toybots'']] with [[Janice Kawaye]] reprising her role as the character.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Jenny also appears as a playable character in the official [[mobile game]] ''Nickelodeon Super Brawl Universe''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0318233|My Life as a Teenage Robot}}\n* {{tv.com show|my-life-as-a-teenage-robot}}\n{{Former Nickelodeon original series}}\n{{Frederator Studios}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Nickelodeon|Animation|Television|United States|Cartoon}}\n\n[[Category:My Life as a Teenage Robot| ]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Nickelodeon shows]]\n[[Category:2003 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2009 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:Child superheroes]]\n[[Category:Robot superheroes]]\n[[Category:Nicktoons]]\n[[Category:Teen superhero television programs]]\n[[Category:Frederator Studios]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about robots]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about teenagers]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about siblings]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Rob Renzetti]]\n[[Category:TNT (Russian TV channel) programs]]\n[[Category:YTV shows]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "2601:704:200:c870:5565:3916:6ce7:2ee5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Life_as_a_Teenage_Robot"}
{"title_page": "Sankarshan Thakur", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''Sankarshan Thakur''' is an Indian print journalist.<ref>[http://www.thesundayindian.com/en/story/like-father-like-son/96/33955/ Like father, like son]</ref><ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111229/jsp/frontpage/story_14938986.jsp#.UxIlvuOSzpw]</ref><ref>http://ibnlive.in.com/news/nitish-is-keeping-his-options-open-at-this-stage-sankarshan-thakur/379630-3.html</ref> He was born in [[Bihar]] in 1962. His work seems deeply inspired by [[M.J. Akbar]], under whom Thakur apprenticed as a journalist for many years. Thakur was the Executive Editor of [[Tehelka]] weekly, which he helped launch in early 2004. He has now returned to [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]], where he started his journalistic career in 1985, as the newspaper's Roving Editor. He was earlier Associate Editor of [[The Indian Express]]. Thakur has covered [[Bihar]] and [[Kashmir]] extensively. Some of his most memorable stories came off the [[Kargil War|Kargil]] warfront in the summer of 1999. He won the [[Prem Bhatia award]] for excellence in political journalism in 2001. In 2003, he won the [[Appan Menon]] Fellowship to work on a book on Kashmir which is in the making.<ref>{{cite news |title=Appan Menon award  |url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/09/18/stories/2003091804011200.htm |publisher=The Hindu |date= Sep 18, 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Thakur is author of a book based on life of [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]] titled as ''The Making of Laloo Yadav, The Unmaking of Bihar'' ({{ISBN|978-8172234003}}); the book was recently updated and reprinted by Picador India under the title \"Subaltern Sahib: Bihar and the Making of Laloo Yadav\".<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/the-godmothers-of-bihar/article1-617030.aspx The godmothers of Bihar]</ref><ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/book-review-of-the-making-of-laloo-yadav/1/244328.html Hell's Angel]</ref> \n*Thakur has also authored a biography of [[Nitish Kumar]] titled ''Single Man: The Life And Times of Nitish Kumar of Bihar''.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-when-nitish-cancelled-the-modi-dinner/20140228.htm When Nitish Kumar cancelled the Modi dinner]</ref><ref>[http://books.rediff.com/book/single-man---the-life-and-times-of-nitish-kumar-of-bihar/9789350297773?sc_cid=rediff_picks Single Man : The Life And Times Of Nitish Kumar Of Bihar]</ref><ref>[http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/9Dpzj5IuYYZlLFOI8etImO/Nitish-Kumar-Bihars-renaissance-man.html Nitish Kumar: Bihar\u2019s renaissance man]</ref><ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-nitish-sees-modi-as-a-man-who-imperils-inclusive-and-secular-india/20140221.htm 'Nitish Kumar sees Narendra Modi as a man who imperils inclusive and secular India']</ref>\n*In November 2015, Thakur's book ''The Brothers Bihari'' featuring a dual biography of Laloo Yadav and Nitish Kumar was released.<ref name=\"IE November 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/books/the-brothers-bihari-a-book-that-charts-journeys-of-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-prasad/ |title=The Brothers Bihari: A book that charts journeys of Nitish Kumar and Lalu Prasad |publisher=Indian Express |date=29 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sankarshanthakur.com/ Official website]\n* [https://sankarshanthakur.com/2012/12/02/who-killed-haren-pandya/ Who Killed Haren Pandya?]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thakur, Sankarshan}}\n[[Category:Indian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Bihar]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''Sankarshan Thakur''' is an Indian print journalist.<ref>[http://www.thesundayindian.com/en/story/like-father-like-son/96/33955/ Like father, like son]</ref><ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111229/jsp/frontpage/story_14938986.jsp#.UxIlvuOSzpw]</ref><ref>http://ibnlive.in.com/news/nitish-is-keeping-his-options-open-at-this-stage-sankarshan-thakur/379630-3.html</ref> He was born in [[Bihar]] in 1962. His work seems deeply inspired by [[M.J. Akbar]], under whom Thakur apprenticed as a journalist for many years. Thakur was the Executive Editor of [[Tehelka]] weekly, which he helped launch in early 2004. He has now returned to [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]], where he started his journalistic career in 1985, as the newspaper's Roving Editor. He was earlier Associate Editor of [[The Indian Express]]. Thakur has covered [[Bihar]] and [[Kashmir]] extensively. Some of his most memorable stories came off the [[Kargil War|Kargil]] warfront in the summer of 1999. He won the [[Prem Bhatia award]] for excellence in political journalism in 2001. In 2003, he won the [[Appan Menon]] Fellowship to work on a book on Kashmir which is in the making.<ref>{{cite news |title=Appan Menon award  |url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/09/18/stories/2003091804011200.htm |publisher=The Hindu |date= Sep 18, 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Thakur is author of a book based on life of [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]] titled as ''The Making of Laloo Yadav, The Unmaking of Bihar'' ({{ISBN|978-8172234003}}); the book was recently updated and reprinted by Picador India under the title \"Subaltern Sahib: Bihar and the Making of Laloo Yadav\".<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/the-godmothers-of-bihar/article1-617030.aspx The godmothers of Bihar]</ref><ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/book-review-of-the-making-of-laloo-yadav/1/244328.html Hell's Angel]</ref> \n*Thakur has also authored a biography of [[Nitish Kumar]] titled ''Single Man: The Life And Times of Nitish Kumar of Bihar''.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-when-nitish-cancelled-the-modi-dinner/20140228.htm When Nitish Kumar cancelled the Modi dinner]</ref><ref>[http://books.rediff.com/book/single-man---the-life-and-times-of-nitish-kumar-of-bihar/9789350297773?sc_cid=rediff_picks Single Man : The Life And Times Of Nitish Kumar Of Bihar]</ref><ref>[http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/9Dpzj5IuYYZlLFOI8etImO/Nitish-Kumar-Bihars-renaissance-man.html Nitish Kumar: Bihar\u2019s renaissance man]</ref><ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-nitish-sees-modi-as-a-man-who-imperils-inclusive-and-secular-india/20140221.htm 'Nitish Kumar sees Narendra Modi as a man who imperils inclusive and secular India']</ref>\n*In November 2015, Thakur's book ''The Brothers Bihari'' featuring a dual biography of Laloo Yadav and Nitish Kumar was released.<ref name=\"IE November 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/books/the-brothers-bihari-a-book-that-charts-journeys-of-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-prasad/ |title=The Brothers Bihari: A book that charts journeys of Nitish Kumar and Lalu Prasad |publisher=Indian Express |date=29 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sankarshanthakur.com/ Official website]\n* [https://sankarshanthakur.com/2012/12/02/who-killed-haren-pandya/ Who Killed Haren Pandya?]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thakur, Sankarshan}}\n[[Category:Indian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Bihar]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sankarshan_Thakur"}
{"title_page": "Hassan-i Sabbah", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| occupation = Leader of [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b state]]\n| image = Asabah2.jpg\n| name = Hassan-i Sabbah\n| title = [[Mawla]] of [[Alamut]]\n| religion = [[Shia Islam]]\n| birth_date = {{circa|1050}}\n| birth_place = [[Qom]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date = {{death date|df=yes|1124|06|12}} (26 Rabi'o-Saani 518)\n| death_place = [[Alamut Castle]], [[Nizari Ismaili State]], [[Iran]]\n| Maddhab = [[Niz\u0101r\u012b]], [[Da'a'im al-Islam]]\n| main_interests = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kalam|Islamic theology]]\n* [[Fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]]\n* [[Sharia|Islamic law]]\n}}\n| influenced = {{plainlist|\n* [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]]\n* [[Kia Bozorg Omid]]\n}}\n}}\n{{Ismailism|Ismaili History}}\n\n'''Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d ''Hasan-i Sabb\u0101h'') or '''Hassan as-Sabb\u0101h''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d ''\u1e24asan a\u1e63-\u1e62abb\u0101\u1e25'') (full name: Hassan bin 'Ali bin Muhammad bin Ja'far bin al-Husayn bin Muhammad bin al-Sabbah al-Himyari)<ref name=\"DF\" /> (c. 1050\u20131124)<ref>{{cite book |last=Frischauer|first=Willi|chapter=Chapter II |title=The Aga Khans |publisher=The Bodley Head |date=1970 |isbn=0-370-01304-2 |page=40}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://iis.ac.uk/encyclopaedia-articles/hasan-sabbah |title=Hasan Sabbah |last1=Daftary|first1=Farhad|last2=Ali-de-Unzaga|first2=Omar|publisher=The Institute of Ismaili Studies|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> was the founder of the [[Nizari Ismaili state|Nizari Isma'ili state]] and its [[fedayeen]] military group<ref name=\":0\">Lewis, Bernard (1967), ''The Assassins: a Radical Sect of Islam'', pp 38-65, Oxford University Press</ref> known as [[Order of Assassins]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hasan-e-Sabbah |title=\u1e24asan-e \u1e62abb\u0101\u1e25 |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |last=Chisholm |first=Hugh |author-link=Hugh Chisholm |year=1911 |edition=11th |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref> (often referred also as the ''Hashshashin).''\n\nHassan-i Sabb\u0101h was a missionary who converted the people of the [[Alborz]] Mountains of northern [[Iran]] to [[Nizari Isma'ilism]] in the late 11th century. He later seized a mountain fortress called [[Alamut Castle|Alamut]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Daftary |first=Farhad |author-link=Farhad Daftary |title=Historical Dictionary of the Ismailis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdLeEkAUoGIC&pg=PA15 |publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]] |year=2012 |page=15 |isbn=9780810861640}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nHassan is thought to have written an autobiography, which did not survive but seems to underlie the first part of an anonymous Isma'ili biography entitled ''Sargozasht-e Seyyedn\u0101'' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0631\u06af\u0630\u0634\u062a \u0633\u06cc\u062f\u0646\u0627}}). The latter is known only from quotations made by later Persian authors.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\">[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Isma'ilis'', p. 311.</ref> Hassan also wrote a treatise, in [[Persian language|Persian]], on the doctrine of ''[[ta'l\u012bm]]'', called, ''al-Fusul al-arba'a''<ref name=\"Daftary2\">[[Farhad Daftary]], ''Ismaili Literature: A Bibliography of Sources and Studies'', (I.B.Tauris, 2004), 115.</ref> The text is no longer in existence, but fragments are cited or paraphrased by [[al-Shahrast\u0101n\u012b]] and several Persian historians.<ref name=\"Daftary2\" />\n\n==Early life and conversion==\n\n===Qom and Rayy===\n[[File:Hasan-e Sabah, rycina, XIX w.jpg|thumb|right|[[Engraving]] of the Elder from the Mountains, as Hassan-i Sabbah was called, 19th century.]]\n\nThe possibly autobiographical information found in ''Sargozasht-i Seyyedn\u0101'' is the main source for Hassan's background and early life. According to this, Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h was born in the city of [[Qom]] (Iran) in the 1050s to a family of [[Twelvers|Twelver]] Sh\u012b\u2018ah.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/> His father, reportedly of [[Qahtanite|Yemenite origins]], had left the Saw\u0101d of [[Kufa]] (modern [[Iraq]]) to settle in the (predominantly Shi'a) town of Qom.<ref name=\"BL\">{{cite book |last=[[Bernard Lewis|Lewis]]|first=[[Bernard Lewis|Bernard]]|chapter=3. The New Preaching |title=The Assassins |publisher=Basic Books |date=November 2002 |isbn=978-0-465-00498-0 |quote=Hasan-i Sabbah was born in the city of Qumm, a stronghold of Twelver Shi'ism. His father, a Twelver Shi'ite, had come from Kufa in Iraq, and was said to be of Yemeni origin.}}</ref><ref name=\"DF\">{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kQGlyZAy134C&pg=PA94&dq=Al-Dibaj&lr=&as_brr=3&cd=11#v=onepage&q=Zaydi%20Imam&f=false|publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=311 |quote=His father, 'Ali b. Muhammad b. Ja'far b. al-Husayn b. Muhammad b. al-Sabbah al-Himyari, a [[Kufa]]n claiming Yamani origins, had migrated from the Sawad of Kufa to the traditionally Shi'i town of Qumm in Persia.}}</ref>\n\nEarly in his life, his family moved to [[Rey, Iran|Rayy]].<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/> Rayy was a city that had a history of radical Islamic thought since the 9th century, with [[Hamedan Qarmat|Hamdan Qarma\u1e6d]] as one of its teachers.\n\nIt was in this religious centre that Hassan developed a keen interest in metaphysical matters and adhered to the Twelver code of instruction. During the day<ref>[[Nizam al-Mulk Tusi]], pg. 420, foot note No. 3</ref> he studied at home, and mastered [[palmistry]], [[languages]], [[philosophy]], [[astronomy]] and [[mathematics]] (especially [[geometry]]).<ref>[[Edward Granville Browne|E. G. Brown]] ''Literary History of Persia'', Vol. 1, p. 201.</ref>\n\nRayy was also the home of Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl\u012b missionaries in the [[Jibal]]. At the time, Isma'ilism was a growing movement in Persia and other lands east of Egypt.<ref name=\"Daftari, pp. 310-11\">[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Isma'ilis'', pp. 310\u201311.</ref> The Persian Isma'ilis supported the ''da'wa'' (\"mission\") directed by the [[Fatimid caliphate]] of [[Cairo]] and recognized the authority of the Imam-Caliph [[Ma'ad al-Mustansir Billah|al-Mustan\u1e63ir]] (d. 1094), though [[Isfahan]], rather than Cairo, may have functioned as their principal headquarters.<ref name=\"Daftari, pp. 310-11\"/> The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b mission worked on three layers: the lowest was the ''[[Fedayeen|fida'i]]'' or foot soldier'','' followed by the ''raf\u012bk'' or comrade, and finally the [[Da'i|''d\u0101\u2018\u012b'']] or missionary. It has been suggested that the popularity of the Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b religion in Persia was due to the people's dissatisfaction with the [[Seljuk dynasty|Seljuk]] rulers, who had recently removed local rulers.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/>\n\nIn Rayy, a young Hassan came in touch with [[Amira Darrab]], a comrade, who introduced him to the Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b doctrine. Although Hassan was initially unimpressed, his interest gradually grew after he participated in many passionate debates that discussed the merits of [[Isma'il ibn Jafar|Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl]] over [[Musa al-Kazim|M\u016bs\u0101]]. Seeing the conviction of Darrab convinced Hassan to delve deeper into Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b doctrines and beliefs, ultimately convincing him to see merit in switching to the Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl\u012b faith.\n\n===Conversion to Ismailism and training in Cairo===\nAt the age of 17, Hassan converted and swore allegiance to the Fatimid caliph in Cairo.  Hassan's studies did not end with his crossing over. He further studied under two other ''d\u0101\u2018iyyayn'', and as he proceeded on his path, he was looked upon with eyes of respect.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHassan's austere and devoted commitment to the ''da'wa'' brought him in audience with the chief missionary of the region: [['Abdu l-Malik ibn Attash]]. Ibn Attash, suitably impressed with the young seventeen-year-old Hassan, made him Deputy Missionary and advised him to go to Cairo to further his studies.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nHowever, Hassan did not go to Cairo. Some historians have postulated that Hassan, following his conversion, was playing host to some members of the Fatimid caliphate, and this was leaked to the anti-Fatimid and anti-Sh\u012b\u2018a [[vizier]] [[Nizam al-Mulk]]. This prompted his abandoning Rayy and heading to Cairo in 1076.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nHassan took about 2 years to reach Cairo. Along the way he toured many other regions that did not fall in the general direction of Egypt.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} Isfahan was the first city that he visited. He was hosted by one of the Missionaries of his youth, a man who had taught the youthful Hassan in Rayy. His name was Resi Abufasl and he further instructed Hassan.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nFrom here he went to Caucasian Albania (current Azerbaijan), hundreds of miles to the north, and from there through Armenia. Here he attracted the ire of priests following a heated discussion, and Hassan was thrown out of the town he was in.\n\nHe then turned south and traveled through Iraq, reached [[Damascus]] in Syria. He left for Egypt from [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]. Records exist, some in the fragmentary remains of his autobiography, and from another biography written by [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]] in 1310, to date his arrival in Egypt at 30 August 1078.\n\nIt is unclear how long Hassan stayed in Egypt: about 3 years is the usually accepted amount of time. He continued his studies here, and became a full missionary.\n\n===Return to Persia===\nWhilst he was in Cairo, studying and preaching, he incurred the displeasure of the Chief of the Army, [[Badr al-Jamali|Badr al-Jamal\u012b]].<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=313}}</ref> This may have been a result of the fact that Hassan supported Nizar, the Ismaili Imam-Caliph [[Ma'ad al-Mustansir Billah|al-Mustan\u1e63ir]]'s elder son, as the next Imam. Hassan was briefly imprisoned by [[Badr al-Jamali]]. The collapse of a minaret of the jail was taken to be an omen in favor of Hassan and he was promptly released and deported.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} The ship that he was traveling on was wrecked. He was rescued and taken to Syria. Traveling via [[Aleppo]] and [[Baghdad]], he terminated his journey at [[Isfahan (city)|Isfahan]] in 1081.\n\nHassan's life now was totally devoted to the mission. Hassan toured extensively throughout Persia. In northern Persia, touching the south shore of the [[Caspian Sea]], are the mountains of [[Alborz]].{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} These mountains were home to a people who had traditionally resisted attempts by both Arabs and Turkish subjugation; this place was also a home of Sh\u012b\u2018a leaning. The news of this Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b's activities reached Nizam al-Mulk, who dispatched his soldiers with the orders for Hassan's capture. Hassan evaded them, and went deeper into the mountains.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\n==Capture of Alamut==\n[[File:Assassins2-alamut.jpg|thumb|The [[Hashshashin]]'s [[fortress]] of [[Alamut Castle]].]]\nHis search for a base from which to guide his mission ended when in 1088 he found the castle of [[Alamut Castle|Alamut]] in the [[Rudbar]] area (modern [[Qazvin]], Iran).{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} It was a fort that stood guard over a valley that was about fifty kilometers long and five kilometers wide.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} This fortress had been built about the year 865; legend has it that it was built by a king who saw his eagle fly up to and perch upon a rock, a propitious omen, the importance of which this king, Wah Sudan ibn Marzuban, understood. Likening the perching of the eagle to a lesson given by it, he called the fort Aluh Amu(kh)t: the \"Eagles' Teaching\".<ref name=\"Daftary 316\">{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kQGlyZAy134C&pg=PA94&dq=Al-Dibaj&lr=&as_brr=3&cd=11#v=onepage&q=Zaydi%20Imam&f=false| publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=316}}</ref>\n\nHassan's takeover of the fort was conducted without any significant bloodshed. To effect this transition Hassan employed a patient and deliberate strategy, one which took the better part of two years to effect. First Hassan sent his ''Da\u02bbiyy\u012bn'' and ''Raf\u012bk''s to win over the villages in the valley, and their inhabitants. Next, key people amongst this populace were converted, and finally, in 1090, Hassan took over the fort by infiltrating it with his converts.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=317}}</ref> Hassan gave the former owner a draft drawn on the name of a wealthy landlord and told him to obtain the promised money from this man; when the landlord saw the draft with Hassan's signature, he immediately paid the amount to the fort's owner, astonishing him.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} Another, probably apocryphal version of the takeover states that Hassan offered 3000 gold dinars to the fort's owner for the amount of land that would fit a buffalo's hide. The terms having been agreed upon, Hassan cut the hide into strips and linked them into a large ring around the perimeter of the fort, whose owner was thus undone by his own greed.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nWhile legend holds that after capturing Alamut Hassan thereafter devoted himself so faithfully to study, that in the nearly 35 years he was there he never left his quarters, excepting only two times when he went up to the roof.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}  This reported isolation is highly doubtful, given his extensive recruiting and organizational involvement in the growing Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b insurrections in Persia and Syria.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |pages=318\u2013324}}</ref> Nonetheless, Hassan was highly educated and was known for austerity, studying, translating, praying, fasting, and directing the activities of the Da\u02bbwa: the propagation of the Nizar\u012b doctrine was headquartered at Alamut. He knew the [[Qur'\u0101n]] by heart, could quote extensively from the texts of most Muslim sects, and apart from philosophy, was well versed in [[mathematics]], [[astronomy]], [[alchemy]], [[medicine]], [[architecture]], and the major scientific disciplines of his time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chnpress.com/news/?section=2&id=2786 |title=Hassan Sabbah Dabbled in Astronomy: Experts |publisher=Chnpress.com |accessdate=30 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017030312/http://www.chnpress.com/news/?section=2 |archivedate=17 October 2011  }}</ref> In a major departure from tradition, Hassan declared Persian to be the language of holy literature for Nizaris, a decision that resulted in all the Nizari Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b literature from Persia, Syria, Afghanistan and Central Asia to be transcribed in Persian for several centuries.<ref name=\"Daftary 316\"/>\n\n==Old Man of the Mountain==\n\nHassan, the founder of [[Nizari]] Isma'ilis in Persia, was designated by [[Marco Polo]] using a Syrian equivalent term known in Europe at that time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amaana.org/history/histaa1.htm |title=A Brief History of Ismailism. Preface |last=Aziz |first=Abualy A |publisher=amaana.org |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> as ''Elder'' or ''Old Man of the Mountain''. [[The Travels of Marco Polo|Polo's travelogue]] (''ca.'' 1300) describes Hassan as a charlatan who devised plots to convert young men to his sect. At the ''court'' of the ''Old Man of the Mountain'' \"they were educated in various languages and customs, courtly etiquette, and trained in martial and other skills\".<ref>{{cite book |last=[[James Wasserman|Wasserman]]|first=[[James Wasserman|James]]|chapter=A Note to the Reader on the Historical Context |title=Templar Heresy: A Story of Gnostic Illumination |publisher=Destiny Books |date=8 August 2017 |isbn=978-1-62055-658-0}}</ref> At Alamut they had \"impressive libraries whose collections included books on various religious traditions, philosophical and scientific texts, and scientific equipment\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://the.ismaili/golden-jubilee/episode-synopses |title=Episode Synopses |publisher=The Ismaili. Islamic Publications Limited |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Xishiji'', a Chinese manuscript completed in 1263, relates a story similar to that of Polo. The sect leaders \"ordered to send assassins to hide in those kingdoms which did not surrender. They stabbed their lords, and women as well, and they died\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://carleton.ca/islamstudies/wp-content/uploads/Proceedings-of-ISC2017.pdf |title=The Mountain without the Old Man: Xishiji on Ismailis. PROCEEDINGS OF THE 2ND INTERNATIONAL ISMAILI STUDIES CONFERENCE |publisher=Carleton University, Canada |date=March 2017 |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> A Nizari assassin is identified as [[Fedayeen|''fida'i'']]  or devotee, \"who offers his life for others or in the service of a particular cause\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/fedai- |title=Fed\u0101\u02be\u012b |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Nizari doctrine==\n\nHistorians and scholars identify Hassan-i Sabbah as the founder of the Nizari [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]] and their doctrine. It developed during the struggle for succession of [[Nizar (Fatimid Imam)|Nizar]] to the Fatimid throne in Cairo that eventually laid the foundation of the [[Nizari Isma'ilism]] [[Shia Islam]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Campbell|first=Anthony|chapter=The Nizari schism \u2013 eleventh century |title=The Assassins of Alamut |publisher=Lulu.com |date=2008 |isbn=978-1-4092-0863-1 }}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} Since then, as a basic element of conservative nature, the [[Imamah (Ismaili doctrine)|Ismaili Imamate]] includes a ''hidden'' imam, in addition to the visible (or ''hazar'', meaning apparent)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ismaili.net/heritage/node/10371 |title=Hazar Imam |last=Mumtaz |first=Ali Tajddin |publisher=Ismaili Electronic Library and Database |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> ''imam of the time'', acting as such in a community. An important task of the latter is the proliferation of the doctrine, and of the undisclosed imam's ''spiritual guidance'', in learning centers having instructors proficient in teaching techniques.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mohammad|first=Miraly N.|title=Faith and World: Contemporary Ismaili Social and Political Thought |publisher=iUniverse |date=2016 |isbn=978-1-4917-8972-8}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\nDevotion of the \"true believers\" having \"absolute faith\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Webel|first=Charles P.|chapter=Depicting the Indescribable: A Brief History of Terrorism |title=Terror, Terrorism, and the Human Condition |publisher=Palgrave MacMillan |date=2004 |isbn=1-4039-6161-1|page=25}}</ref> in the beliefs is another element originating from the times of Sabbah in [[Northern Iran]],<ref>{{cite book |last=DTIC|first=US Army|chapter=Terror in Antiquity: First to Fourteenth Century A.D. |title=A Military Guide to Terrorism in the Twenty-First Century. U.S. Army DCSINT Handbook No. 1 (Version 3.0) |publisher=Defense Technical Information Center |date=2005}}</ref> who \"was so devout that he even had one of his sons executed after he was accused of drunkenness\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crenshaw|first1=Martha|last2=Pimlott|first2=John|chapter=The Assassins: a terror cult |title=International Encyclopedia of Terrorism |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |date=1997 |isbn=1-57958-022-X}}</ref>\n\n== Representation in music and popular culture ==\n* A song on [[Hawkwind]]'s 1977 album ''[[Quark, Strangeness and Charm]]'' is titled Hassan I Sabbah.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n* A 1938 novel named ''[[Alamut (Bartol novel)|Alamut]]'' by [[Vladimir Bartol]] is based on Hassan's rise to power.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bassas |first=Carlos |title=Assassin's Creed |url=http://www.diariodenavarra.es/blogs/fuera-de-campo/2016/12/29/assassins-creed/ |date=29 December 2016 |access-date=5 February 2018 |newspaper=[[Diario de Navarra]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Rad |first=Chloi |title=11 videojuegos que no sab\u00edas que est\u00e1n basados en libros |url=http://latam.ign.com/videojuegos/37320/feature/11-videojuegos-que-no-sabias-que-estan-basados-en-libros |date=27 December 2017 |access-date=5 February 2018 |journal=[[IGN]] |language=es}}</ref>\n* Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h is mentioned, often by his moniker 'The Old Man of the Mountain', in many of [[William S. Burroughs]]'s novels, including ''[[Nova Express]]'', ''[[Cities of the Red Night]]'',<ref>'\"Nothing is true, everything is permitted.\" The last words of Hassan i Sabbah, the Old Man of the Mountain.' William S. Burroughs. ''Cities of the Red Night'' (New York: Henry Holt and Company, 2013 [1981]). p. 158</ref> ''[[The Place of Dead Roads]]'' and ''[[The Western Lands]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=Nova Express |editor-last=Kuhlman |editor-first=Roy |editor-link=Roy Kuhlman |publisher=[[Grove Press]] |year=1964|title-link=Nova Express }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=Cities of the Red Night |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1981 |isbn=0-312-27846-2 |oclc=46887518|title-link=Cities of the Red Night }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=The Place of Dead Roads |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1983 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/placeofdeadroads00burr/page/306 306] |isbn=0-03-070416-2 |oclc=9489103 |title-link=The Place of Dead Roads }}</ref><ref>Burroughs, William S. The Western Lands. Viking, 1988.</ref>\n* Hassan is also mentioned in the accompanying story to ''The Rock of Alamut'', a 1000 piece [[jigsaw puzzle]] by Nadirshah Mackwani.<ref>{{cite news |last=Simerg.com |title=Alamut: A 1000 Piece Jigsaw Puzzle by Nadirshah Mackwani|url=https://simerg.com/2012/11/23/alamut-a-1000-piece-jigsaw-puzzle-by-nadirshah-mackwani/ |access-date=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n* There are various Assassin class Servants who go by the name of \"Hassan-i Sabbah\" in the ''[[Fate/stay night]]'' anime and visual novel franchise, most notably in ''[[Fate/Zero]]'', and the ''Heaven's Feel'' Route of ''Fate/stay night'', where they appear as antagonists.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} However they appear as allied protagonists in the mobile game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]'', particularly during the Camelot chapter. Hassan himself, identified as the \"First Hassan\", is also present in the game. It is established that \"Hassan-i Sabbah\" is a title used by each of the nineteen leaders of the Hashshashin.\n* The album ''[[In the Absence of Truth]]'' by [[ISIS (band)|ISIS]] draws inspiration from Hassan-i Sabbah.\n*Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h is one of the characters in [[Amin Maalouf]]'s novel [[Samarkand (novel)|''Samarkand'']].\n* Attributed in [[Phil Hine]]'s book Condensed Chaos and in the [[chaos magic]] scene with the quote, \"Nothing is true, everything is permitted.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Hine |first=Phil |author-link=Phil Hine |page=24 |section=Fractal Logic |title=Condensed Chaos |publisher=The Original Falcon Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-1-935150-66-4}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Firdaws-i Bareen]]\n*[[Aga Khan IV]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Firdous-a-iblees by anayat ullah\n\n===Secondary sources===\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The [[Isma'ili]]s: Their History and Doctrines''. 2nd ed (1990). Cambridge et al., 2007.\n* Irwin, Robert. \"Islam and the Crusades, 1096\u20131699\". In ''The Oxford History of the Crusades'', ed. Jonathan Riley Smith. Oxford, 2002. 211\u201357.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Firdous-e-Iblees by Anayat Ullah\n*Hasan-I-Sabbah: His Life and Thought by Dr. Ali Mohammad Rajput\n\n===Primary sources===\n*Hassan-i Sabbah, ''al-Fu\u1e63\u016bl al-arba'a'' (\"The Four Chapters\"), tr. [[Marshall Hodgson|Marshall G.S. Hodgson]], in ''Ismaili Literature Anthology. A Shi'i Vision of Islam'', ed. Hermann Landolt, Samira Sheikh and Kutub Kassam. London, 2008. pp.&nbsp;149\u201352. [[Persian language|Persian]] treatise on the doctrine of ''[[ta'l\u012bm]]''. The text is no longer extant, but fragments are cited or paraphrased by [[al-Shahrast\u0101n\u012b]] and several Persian historians.\n*''Sarguzasht-e Sayyidn\u0101''\n*[[Nizam al-Mulk]]\n*[[al-Ghazali]]\n\n===Secondary sources===\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''A Short History of the [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]]s''. Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1998.\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Assassin Legends: Myths of the [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]]s''. London: I.B. Tauris & Co. Ltd, 1994. [http://www.ismaili.net/Source/fd0328d.html Reviewed by Babak Nahid at Ismaili.net]\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], \"Hasan-i Sabb\u0101h and the Origins of the [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] movement.\" In ''Mediaeval [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] History and Thought'', ed. [[Farhad Daftary]]. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1996. 181\u2013204.\n* [[Marshall Hodgson|Hodgson, Marshall]], ''The Order of [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]]. The Struggle of the Early [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] Against the Islamic World''. The Hague: Mouton, 1955.\n* [[Marshall Hodgson|Hodgson, Marshall]], \"The [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] State.\" In ''The Cambridge History of Iran'', vol. 5: ''The Saljuq and Mongol Periods'', ed. J.A. Boyle. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1968. 422\u201382.\n* [[Bernard Lewis|Lewis, Bernard]], ''The [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]]. A Radical Sect in Islam''. New York: Basic Books, 1968.\n* [[Wilferd Madelung|Madelung, Wilferd]], ''Religious Trends in Early Islamic Iran''. Albany: Bibliotheca Persica, 1988. 101\u20135.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ismaili.net/histoire/history06/history601.html HASAN BIN SABBAH AND NIZARI ISMAILI STATE IN ALAMUT]\n* [http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_article.asp?ContentID=110462 The life of Hassan-i-Sabah from an Ismaili point of view.] Focuses on assassination as a tactic of [[asymmetrical warfare]] and has a small section on Hasan-i-Sabah's work as a scholar.\n* [http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_article.asp?ContentID=101164 Introduction to The Assassin Legends] (From The Assassin Legends: Myths of the Isma\u2018ilis, London: I. B. Tauris, 1994; reprinted 2001.)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316145448/http://www.accampbell.uklinux.net/assassins/assassins-html/hasan.html The life of Hassan-i-Sabbah as part of an online book on the Assassins of Alamut.]\n* [http://www.phinnweb.org/neuro/assassins.html Arkon Daraul on Hassan-i-Sabbah.]\n* [http://www.skewsme.com/assassin.html An illustrated article on the Order of Assassins.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830112208/http://www.linesofadvance.com/nova.html William S. Burrough's invocation of Hassan-i-Sabbah in ''Nova Express''.]\n* [http://lexicorient.com/e.o/assassins.htm Assassins entry in the ''Encyclopedia of the Orient''.]\n* [http://www.ismaili.net/Source/fd0328d.html Review of the book, \"The Assassin Legends: Myths of the Isma'ilis (I. B. Tauris & Co. Ltd: London, 1994), 213 pp.\"] by Babak Nahid, Department of Comparative Literature, University of California, Los Angeles\n* [https://the.ismaili/imams-and-their-love-knowledge-0 ''Ismaili Imams and their Love for Knowledge''. Islamic Publications Limited]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sabah, Hassan}}\n[[Category:1050s births]]\n[[Category:1124 deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Muslims]]\n[[Category:12th-century Muslims]]\n[[Category:Ismailis]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:People from Alamut]]\n[[Category:People from Qom]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the Fatimid Caliphate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| occupation = Leader of [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b state]]\n| image = Asabah2.jpg\n| name = Hassan-i Sabbah\n| title = [[Mawla]] of [[Alamut]]\n| religion = [[Shia Islam]]\n| birth_date = {{circa|1050}}\n| birth_place = [[Qom]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date = {{death date|df=yes|1124|06|12}} (26 Rabi'o-Saani 518)\n| death_place = [[Alamut Castle]], [[Nizari Ismaili State]], [[Iran]]\n| Maddhab = [[Niz\u0101r\u012b]], [[Da'a'im al-Islam]]\n| main_interests = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kalam|Islamic theology]]\n* [[Fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]]\n* [[Sharia|Islamic law]]\n}}\n| influenced = {{plainlist|\n* [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]]\n* [[Kia Bozorg Omid]]\n}}\n}}\n{{Ismailism|Ismaili History}}\n\n'''Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d ''Hasan-i Sabb\u0101h'') or '''Hassan as-Sabb\u0101h''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d ''\u1e24asan a\u1e63-\u1e62abb\u0101\u1e25'') (full name: Hassan bin 'Ali bin Muhammad bin Ja'far bin al-Husayn bin Muhammad bin al-Sabbah al-Himyari)<ref name=\"DF\" /> (c. 1050\u20131124)<ref>{{cite book |last=Frischauer|first=Willi|chapter=Chapter II |title=The Aga Khans |publisher=The Bodley Head |date=1970 |isbn=0-370-01304-2 |page=40}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://iis.ac.uk/encyclopaedia-articles/hasan-sabbah |title=Hasan Sabbah |last1=Daftary|first1=Farhad|last2=Ali-de-Unzaga|first2=Omar|publisher=The Institute of Ismaili Studies|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> was the founder of the [[Nizari Ismaili state|Nizari Isma'ili state]] and its [[fedayeen]] military group<ref name=\":0\">Lewis, Bernard (1967), ''The Assassins: a Radical Sect of Islam'', pp 38-65, Oxford University Press</ref> known as [[Order of Assassins]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hasan-e-Sabbah |title=\u1e24asan-e \u1e62abb\u0101\u1e25 |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |last=Chisholm |first=Hugh |author-link=Hugh Chisholm |year=1911 |edition=11th |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref> (often referred also as the ''Hashshashin).''\n\nHassan-i Sabb\u0101h was a missionary who converted the people of the [[Alborz]] Mountains of northern [[Iran]] to [[Nizari Isma'ilism]] in the late 11th century. He later seized a mountain fortress called [[Alamut Castle|Alamut]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Daftary |first=Farhad |author-link=Farhad Daftary |title=Historical Dictionary of the Ismailis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdLeEkAUoGIC&pg=PA15 |publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]] |year=2012 |page=15 |isbn=9780810861640}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\nHassan is thought to have written an autobiography, which did not survive but seems to underlie the first part of an anonymous Isma'ili biography entitled ''Sargozasht-e Seyyedn\u0101'' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0631\u06af\u0630\u0634\u062a \u0633\u06cc\u062f\u0646\u0627}}). The latter is known only from quotations made by later Persian authors.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\">[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Isma'ilis'', p. 311.</ref> Hassan also wrote a treatise, in [[Persian language|Persian]], on the doctrine of ''[[ta'l\u012bm]]'', called, ''al-Fusul al-arba'a''<ref name=\"Daftary2\">[[Farhad Daftary]], ''Ismaili Literature: A Bibliography of Sources and Studies'', (I.B.Tauris, 2004), 115.</ref> The text is no longer in existence, but fragments are cited or paraphrased by [[al-Shahrast\u0101n\u012b]] and several Persian historians.<ref name=\"Daftary2\" />\n\n==Early life and conversion==\n\n===Qom and Rayy===\n[[File:Hasan-e Sabah, rycina, XIX w.jpg|thumb|right|[[Engraving]] of the Elder from the Mountains, as Hassan-i Sabbah was called, 19th century.]]\n\nThe possibly autobiographical information found in ''Sargozasht-i Seyyedn\u0101'' is the main source for Hassan's background and early life. According to this, Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h was born in the city of [[Qom]] (Iran) in the 1050s to a family of [[Twelvers|Twelver]] Sh\u012b\u2018ah.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/> His father, reportedly of [[Qahtanite|Yemenite origins]], had left the Saw\u0101d of [[Kufa]] (modern [[Iraq]]) to settle in the (predominantly Shi'a) town of Qom.<ref name=\"BL\">{{cite book |last=[[Bernard Lewis|Lewis]]|first=[[Bernard Lewis|Bernard]]|chapter=3. The New Preaching |title=The Assassins |publisher=Basic Books |date=November 2002 |isbn=978-0-465-00498-0 |quote=Hasan-i Sabbah was born in the city of Qumm, a stronghold of Twelver Shi'ism. His father, a Twelver Shi'ite, had come from Kufa in Iraq, and was said to be of Yemeni origin.}}</ref><ref name=\"DF\">{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kQGlyZAy134C&pg=PA94&dq=Al-Dibaj&lr=&as_brr=3&cd=11#v=onepage&q=Zaydi%20Imam&f=false|publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=311 |quote=His father, 'Ali b. Muhammad b. Ja'far b. al-Husayn b. Muhammad b. al-Sabbah al-Himyari, a [[Kufa]]n claiming Yamani origins, had migrated from the Sawad of Kufa to the traditionally Shi'i town of Qumm in Persia.}}</ref>\n\nEarly in his life, his family moved to [[Rey, Iran|Rayy]].<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/> Rayy was a city that had a history of radical Islamic thought since the 9th century, with [[Hamedan Qarmat|Hamdan Qarma\u1e6d]] as one of its teachers.\n\nIt was in this religious centre that Hassan developed a keen interest in metaphysical matters and adhered to the Twelver code of instruction. During the day<ref>[[Nizam al-Mulk Tusi]], pg. 420, foot note No. 3</ref> he studied at home, and mastered [[palmistry]], [[languages]], [[philosophy]], [[astronomy]] and [[mathematics]] (especially [[geometry]]).<ref>[[Edward Granville Browne|E. G. Brown]] ''Literary History of Persia'', Vol. 1, p. 201.</ref>\n\nRayy was also the home of Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl\u012b missionaries in the [[Jibal]]. At the time, Isma'ilism was a growing movement in Persia and other lands east of Egypt.<ref name=\"Daftari, pp. 310-11\">[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Isma'ilis'', pp. 310\u201311.</ref> The Persian Isma'ilis supported the ''da'wa'' (\"mission\") directed by the [[Fatimid caliphate]] of [[Cairo]] and recognized the authority of the Imam-Caliph [[Ma'ad al-Mustansir Billah|al-Mustan\u1e63ir]] (d. 1094), though [[Isfahan]], rather than Cairo, may have functioned as their principal headquarters.<ref name=\"Daftari, pp. 310-11\"/> The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b mission worked on three layers: the lowest was the ''[[Fedayeen|fida'i]]'' or foot soldier'','' followed by the ''raf\u012bk'' or comrade, and finally the [[Da'i|''d\u0101\u2018\u012b'']] or missionary. It has been suggested that the popularity of the Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b religion in Persia was due to the people's dissatisfaction with the [[Seljuk dynasty|Seljuk]] rulers, who had recently removed local rulers.<ref name=\"Daftari, p. 311\"/>\n\nIn Rayy, a young Hassan came in touch with [[Amira Darrab]], a comrade, who introduced him to the Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b doctrine. Although Hassan was initially unimpressed, his interest gradually grew after he participated in many passionate debates that discussed the merits of [[Isma'il ibn Jafar|Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl]] over [[Musa al-Kazim|M\u016bs\u0101]]. Seeing the conviction of Darrab convinced Hassan to delve deeper into Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b doctrines and beliefs, ultimately convincing him to see merit in switching to the Ism\u0101\u2018\u012bl\u012b faith.\n\n===Conversion to Ismailism and training in Cairo===\nAt the age of 17, Hassan converted and swore allegiance to the Fatimid caliph in Cairo.  Hassan's studies did not end with his crossing over. He further studied under two other ''d\u0101\u2018iyyayn'', and as he proceeded on his path, he was looked upon with eyes of respect.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHassan's austere and devoted commitment to the ''da'wa'' brought him in audience with the chief missionary of the region: [['Abdu l-Malik ibn Attash]]. Ibn Attash, suitably impressed with the young seventeen-year-old Hassan, made him Deputy Missionary and advised him to go to Cairo to further his studies.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nHowever, Hassan did not go to Cairo. Some historians have postulated that Hassan, following his conversion, was playing host to some members of the Fatimid caliphate, and this was leaked to the anti-Fatimid and anti-Sh\u012b\u2018a [[vizier]] [[Nizam al-Mulk]]. This prompted his abandoning Rayy and heading to Cairo in 1076.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nHassan took about 2 years to reach Cairo. Along the way he toured many other regions that did not fall in the general direction of Egypt.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} Isfahan was the first city that he visited. He was hosted by one of the Missionaries of his youth, a man who had taught the youthful Hassan in Rayy. His name was Resi Abufasl and he further instructed Hassan.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nFrom here he went to Caucasian Albania (current Azerbaijan), hundreds of miles to the north, and from there through Armenia. Here he attracted the ire of priests following a heated discussion, and Hassan was thrown out of the town he was in.\n\nHe then turned south and traveled through Iraq, reached [[Damascus]] in Syria. He left for Egypt from [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]. Records exist, some in the fragmentary remains of his autobiography, and from another biography written by [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]] in 1310, to date his arrival in Egypt at 30 August 1078.\n\nIt is unclear how long Hassan stayed in Egypt: about 3 years is the usually accepted amount of time. He continued his studies here, and became a full missionary.\n\n===Return to Persia===\nWhilst he was in Cairo, studying and preaching, he incurred the displeasure of the Chief of the Army, [[Badr al-Jamali|Badr al-Jamal\u012b]].<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=313}}</ref> This may have been a result of the fact that Hassan supported Nizar, the Ismaili Imam-Caliph [[Ma'ad al-Mustansir Billah|al-Mustan\u1e63ir]]'s elder son, as the next Imam. Hassan was briefly imprisoned by [[Badr al-Jamali]]. The collapse of a minaret of the jail was taken to be an omen in favor of Hassan and he was promptly released and deported.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} The ship that he was traveling on was wrecked. He was rescued and taken to Syria. Traveling via [[Aleppo]] and [[Baghdad]], he terminated his journey at [[Isfahan (city)|Isfahan]] in 1081.\n\nHassan's life now was totally devoted to the mission. Hassan toured extensively throughout Persia. In northern Persia, touching the south shore of the [[Caspian Sea]], are the mountains of [[Alborz]].{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} These mountains were home to a people who had traditionally resisted attempts by both Arabs and Turkish subjugation; this place was also a home of Sh\u012b\u2018a leaning. The news of this Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b's activities reached Nizam al-Mulk, who dispatched his soldiers with the orders for Hassan's capture. Hassan evaded them, and went deeper into the mountains.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\n==Capture of Alamut==\n[[File:Assassins2-alamut.jpg|thumb|The [[Hashshashin]]'s [[fortress]] of [[Alamut Castle]].]]\nHis search for a base from which to guide his mission ended when in 1088 he found the castle of [[Alamut Castle|Alamut]] in the [[Rudbar]] area (modern [[Qazvin]], Iran).{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} It was a fort that stood guard over a valley that was about fifty kilometers long and five kilometers wide.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} This fortress had been built about the year 865; legend has it that it was built by a king who saw his eagle fly up to and perch upon a rock, a propitious omen, the importance of which this king, Wah Sudan ibn Marzuban, understood. Likening the perching of the eagle to a lesson given by it, he called the fort Aluh Amu(kh)t: the \"Eagles' Teaching\".<ref name=\"Daftary 316\">{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kQGlyZAy134C&pg=PA94&dq=Al-Dibaj&lr=&as_brr=3&cd=11#v=onepage&q=Zaydi%20Imam&f=false| publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=316}}</ref>\n\nHassan's takeover of the fort was conducted without any significant bloodshed. To effect this transition Hassan employed a patient and deliberate strategy, one which took the better part of two years to effect. First Hassan sent his ''Da\u02bbiyy\u012bn'' and ''Raf\u012bk''s to win over the villages in the valley, and their inhabitants. Next, key people amongst this populace were converted, and finally, in 1090, Hassan took over the fort by infiltrating it with his converts.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |page=317}}</ref> Hassan gave the former owner a draft drawn on the name of a wealthy landlord and told him to obtain the promised money from this man; when the landlord saw the draft with Hassan's signature, he immediately paid the amount to the fort's owner, astonishing him.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} Another, probably apocryphal version of the takeover states that Hassan offered 3000 gold dinars to the fort's owner for the amount of land that would fit a buffalo's hide. The terms having been agreed upon, Hassan cut the hide into strips and linked them into a large ring around the perimeter of the fort, whose owner was thus undone by his own greed.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nWhile legend holds that after capturing Alamut Hassan thereafter devoted himself so faithfully to study, that in the nearly 35 years he was there he never left his quarters, excepting only two times when he went up to the roof.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}  This reported isolation is highly doubtful, given his extensive recruiting and organizational involvement in the growing Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b insurrections in Persia and Syria.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Farhad Daftary|Daftary]]|first=[[Farhad Daftary|Farhad]]|chapter=Nizari Isma'ili history during the Alamut period |title=The Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs: Their History and Doctrines 2nd Edition |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=September 2007 |isbn=978-0-521-61636-2 |pages=318\u2013324}}</ref> Nonetheless, Hassan was highly educated and was known for austerity, studying, translating, praying, fasting, and directing the activities of the Da\u02bbwa: the propagation of the Nizar\u012b doctrine was headquartered at Alamut. He knew the [[Qur'\u0101n]] by heart, could quote extensively from the texts of most Muslim sects, and apart from philosophy, was well versed in [[mathematics]], [[astronomy]], [[alchemy]], [[medicine]], [[architecture]], and the major scientific disciplines of his time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chnpress.com/news/?section=2&id=2786 |title=Hassan Sabbah Dabbled in Astronomy: Experts |publisher=Chnpress.com |accessdate=30 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017030312/http://www.chnpress.com/news/?section=2 |archivedate=17 October 2011  }}</ref> In a major departure from tradition, Hassan declared Persian to be the language of holy literature for Nizaris, a decision that resulted in all the Nizari Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b literature from Persia, Syria, Afghanistan and Central Asia to be transcribed in Persian for several centuries.<ref name=\"Daftary 316\"/>\n\n==Old Man of the Mountain==\n\nHassan, the founder of [[Nizari]] Isma'ilis in Persia, was designated by [[Marco Polo]] using a Syrian equivalent term known in Europe at that time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amaana.org/history/histaa1.htm |title=A Brief History of Ismailism. Preface |last=Aziz |first=Abualy A |publisher=amaana.org |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> as ''Elder'' or ''Old Man of the Mountain''. [[The Travels of Marco Polo|Polo's travelogue]] (''ca.'' 1300) describes Hassan as a charlatan who devised plots to convert young men to his sect. At the ''court'' of the ''Old Man of the Mountain'' \"they were educated in various languages and customs, courtly etiquette, and trained in martial and other skills\".<ref>{{cite book |last=[[James Wasserman|Wasserman]]|first=[[James Wasserman|James]]|chapter=A Note to the Reader on the Historical Context |title=Templar Heresy: A Story of Gnostic Illumination |publisher=Destiny Books |date=8 August 2017 |isbn=978-1-62055-658-0}}</ref> At Alamut they had \"impressive libraries whose collections included books on various religious traditions, philosophical and scientific texts, and scientific equipment\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://the.ismaili/golden-jubilee/episode-synopses |title=Episode Synopses |publisher=The Ismaili. Islamic Publications Limited |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Xishiji'', a Chinese manuscript completed in 1263, relates a story similar to that of Polo. The sect leaders \"ordered to send assassins to hide in those kingdoms which did not surrender. They stabbed their lords, and women as well, and they died\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://carleton.ca/islamstudies/wp-content/uploads/Proceedings-of-ISC2017.pdf |title=The Mountain without the Old Man: Xishiji on Ismailis. PROCEEDINGS OF THE 2ND INTERNATIONAL ISMAILI STUDIES CONFERENCE |publisher=Carleton University, Canada |date=March 2017 |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> A Nizari assassin is identified as [[Fedayeen|''fida'i'']]  or devotee, \"who offers his life for others or in the service of a particular cause\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/fedai- |title=Fed\u0101\u02be\u012b |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Nizari doctrine==\n\nHistorians and scholars identify Hassan-i Sabbah as the founder of the Nizari [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]] and their doctrine. It developed during the struggle for succession of [[Nizar (Fatimid Imam)|Nizar]] to the Fatimid throne in Cairo that eventually laid the foundation of the [[Nizari Isma'ilism]] [[Shia Islam]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Campbell|first=Anthony|chapter=The Nizari schism \u2013 eleventh century |title=The Assassins of Alamut |publisher=Lulu.com |date=2008 |isbn=978-1-4092-0863-1 }}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} Since then, as a basic element of conservative nature, the [[Imamah (Ismaili doctrine)|Ismaili Imamate]] includes a ''hidden'' imam, in addition to the visible (or ''hazar'', meaning apparent)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ismaili.net/heritage/node/10371 |title=Hazar Imam |last=Mumtaz |first=Ali Tajddin |publisher=Ismaili Electronic Library and Database |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> ''imam of the time'', acting as such in a community. An important task of the latter is the proliferation of the doctrine, and of the undisclosed imam's ''spiritual guidance'', in learning centers having instructors proficient in teaching techniques.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mohammad|first=Miraly N.|title=Faith and World: Contemporary Ismaili Social and Political Thought |publisher=iUniverse |date=2016 |isbn=978-1-4917-8972-8}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\nDevotion of the \"true believers\" having \"absolute faith\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Webel|first=Charles P.|chapter=Depicting the Indescribable: A Brief History of Terrorism |title=Terror, Terrorism, and the Human Condition |publisher=Palgrave MacMillan |date=2004 |isbn=1-4039-6161-1|page=25}}</ref> in the beliefs is another element originating from the times of Sabbah in [[Northern Iran]],<ref>{{cite book |last=DTIC|first=US Army|chapter=Terror in Antiquity: First to Fourteenth Century A.D. |title=A Military Guide to Terrorism in the Twenty-First Century. U.S. Army DCSINT Handbook No. 1 (Version 3.0) |publisher=Defense Technical Information Center |date=2005}}</ref> who \"was so devout that he even had one of his sons executed after he was accused of drunkenness\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crenshaw|first1=Martha|last2=Pimlott|first2=John|chapter=The Assassins: a terror cult |title=International Encyclopedia of Terrorism |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |date=1997 |isbn=1-57958-022-X}}</ref>\n\n== Representation in music and popular culture ==\n* A song on [[Hawkwind]]'s 1977 album ''[[Quark, Strangeness and Charm]]'' is titled Hassan I Sabbah.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n* A 1938 novel named ''[[Alamut (Bartol novel)|Alamut]]'' by [[Vladimir Bartol]] is based on Hassan's rise to power.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bassas |first=Carlos |title=Assassin's Creed |url=http://www.diariodenavarra.es/blogs/fuera-de-campo/2016/12/29/assassins-creed/ |date=29 December 2016 |access-date=5 February 2018 |newspaper=[[Diario de Navarra]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Rad |first=Chloi |title=11 videojuegos que no sab\u00edas que est\u00e1n basados en libros |url=http://latam.ign.com/videojuegos/37320/feature/11-videojuegos-que-no-sabias-que-estan-basados-en-libros |date=27 December 2017 |access-date=5 February 2018 |journal=[[IGN]] |language=es}}</ref>\n* Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h is mentioned, often by his moniker 'The Old Man of the Mountain', in many of [[William S. Burroughs]]'s novels, including ''[[Nova Express]]'', ''[[Cities of the Red Night]]'',<ref>'\"Nothing is true, everything is permitted.\" The last words of Hassan i Sabbah, the Old Man of the Mountain.' William S. Burroughs. ''Cities of the Red Night'' (New York: Henry Holt and Company, 2013 [1981]). p. 158</ref> ''[[The Place of Dead Roads]]'' and ''[[The Western Lands]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=Nova Express |editor-last=Kuhlman |editor-first=Roy |editor-link=Roy Kuhlman |publisher=[[Grove Press]] |year=1964|title-link=Nova Express }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=Cities of the Red Night |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1981 |isbn=0-312-27846-2 |oclc=46887518|title-link=Cities of the Red Night }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Burroughs |first=William S. |author-link=William S. Burroughs |title=The Place of Dead Roads |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |year=1983 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/placeofdeadroads00burr/page/306 306] |isbn=0-03-070416-2 |oclc=9489103 |title-link=The Place of Dead Roads }}</ref><ref>Burroughs, William S. The Western Lands. Viking, 1988.</ref>\n* Hassan is also mentioned in the accompanying story to ''The Rock of Alamut'', a 1000 piece [[jigsaw puzzle]] by Nadirshah Mackwani.<ref>{{cite news |last=Simerg.com |title=Alamut: A 1000 Piece Jigsaw Puzzle by Nadirshah Mackwani|url=https://simerg.com/2012/11/23/alamut-a-1000-piece-jigsaw-puzzle-by-nadirshah-mackwani/ |access-date=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n* There are various Assassin class Servants who go by the name of \"Hassan-i Sabbah\" in the ''[[Fate/stay night]]'' anime and visual novel franchise, most notably in ''[[Fate/Zero]]'', and the ''Heaven's Feel'' Route of ''Fate/stay night'', where they appear as antagonists.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} However they appear as allied protagonists in the mobile game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]'', particularly during the Camelot chapter. Hassan himself, identified as the \"First Hassan\", is also present in the game. It is established that \"Hassan-i Sabbah\" is a title used by each of the nineteen leaders of the Hashshashin.\n* The album ''[[In the Absence of Truth]]'' by [[ISIS (band)|ISIS]] draws inspiration from Hassan-i Sabbah.\n*Hassan-i Sabb\u0101h is one of the characters in [[Amin Maalouf]]'s novel [[Samarkand (novel)|''Samarkand'']].\n* Attributed in [[Phil Hine]]'s book Condensed Chaos and in the [[Chaos Magic]] scene with the quote, \"Nothing is true, everything is permitted.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Hine |first=Phil |author-link=Phil Hine |page=24 |section=Fractal Logic |title=Condensed Chaos |publisher=The Original Falcon Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-1-935150-66-4}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Firdaws-i Bareen]]\n*[[Aga Khan IV]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Firdous-a-iblees by anayat ullah\n\n===Secondary sources===\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The [[Isma'ili]]s: Their History and Doctrines''. 2nd ed (1990). Cambridge et al., 2007.\n* Irwin, Robert. \"Islam and the Crusades, 1096\u20131699\". In ''The Oxford History of the Crusades'', ed. Jonathan Riley Smith. Oxford, 2002. 211\u201357.\n\n==Further reading==\n*Firdous-e-Iblees by Anayat Ullah\n*Hasan-I-Sabbah: His Life and Thought by Dr. Ali Mohammad Rajput\n\n===Primary sources===\n*Hassan-i Sabbah, ''al-Fu\u1e63\u016bl al-arba'a'' (\"The Four Chapters\"), tr. [[Marshall Hodgson|Marshall G.S. Hodgson]], in ''Ismaili Literature Anthology. A Shi'i Vision of Islam'', ed. Hermann Landolt, Samira Sheikh and Kutub Kassam. London, 2008. pp.&nbsp;149\u201352. [[Persian language|Persian]] treatise on the doctrine of ''[[ta'l\u012bm]]''. The text is no longer extant, but fragments are cited or paraphrased by [[al-Shahrast\u0101n\u012b]] and several Persian historians.\n*''Sarguzasht-e Sayyidn\u0101''\n*[[Nizam al-Mulk]]\n*[[al-Ghazali]]\n\n===Secondary sources===\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''A Short History of the [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]]s''. Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1998.\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], ''The Assassin Legends: Myths of the [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]]s''. London: I.B. Tauris & Co. Ltd, 1994. [http://www.ismaili.net/Source/fd0328d.html Reviewed by Babak Nahid at Ismaili.net]\n* [[Farhad Daftary|Daftary, Farhad]], \"Hasan-i Sabb\u0101h and the Origins of the [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] movement.\" In ''Mediaeval [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] History and Thought'', ed. [[Farhad Daftary]]. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1996. 181\u2013204.\n* [[Marshall Hodgson|Hodgson, Marshall]], ''The Order of [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]]. The Struggle of the Early [[Niz\u0101r\u012b Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] Against the Islamic World''. The Hague: Mouton, 1955.\n* [[Marshall Hodgson|Hodgson, Marshall]], \"The [[Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b]] State.\" In ''The Cambridge History of Iran'', vol. 5: ''The Saljuq and Mongol Periods'', ed. J.A. Boyle. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1968. 422\u201382.\n* [[Bernard Lewis|Lewis, Bernard]], ''The [[Order of Assassins|Assassins]]. A Radical Sect in Islam''. New York: Basic Books, 1968.\n* [[Wilferd Madelung|Madelung, Wilferd]], ''Religious Trends in Early Islamic Iran''. Albany: Bibliotheca Persica, 1988. 101\u20135.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ismaili.net/histoire/history06/history601.html HASAN BIN SABBAH AND NIZARI ISMAILI STATE IN ALAMUT]\n* [http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_article.asp?ContentID=110462 The life of Hassan-i-Sabah from an Ismaili point of view.] Focuses on assassination as a tactic of [[asymmetrical warfare]] and has a small section on Hasan-i-Sabah's work as a scholar.\n* [http://www.iis.ac.uk/view_article.asp?ContentID=101164 Introduction to The Assassin Legends] (From The Assassin Legends: Myths of the Isma\u2018ilis, London: I. B. Tauris, 1994; reprinted 2001.)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316145448/http://www.accampbell.uklinux.net/assassins/assassins-html/hasan.html The life of Hassan-i-Sabbah as part of an online book on the Assassins of Alamut.]\n* [http://www.phinnweb.org/neuro/assassins.html Arkon Daraul on Hassan-i-Sabbah.]\n* [http://www.skewsme.com/assassin.html An illustrated article on the Order of Assassins.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050830112208/http://www.linesofadvance.com/nova.html William S. Burrough's invocation of Hassan-i-Sabbah in ''Nova Express''.]\n* [ht