f [[Michael Jordan]]\n|December 14, 2017\n|-\n|2\n|[[Patrick Ewing]] and the Frozen Envelope\n|December 21, 2017\n|-\n|3\n|The Strange Case of [[Deflategate]]\n|December 28, 2017\n|-\n|4\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] and the Phantom Punch\n|January 4, 2018\n|-\n|5\n|The Notorious Game 6 of Lakers vs. Kings\n|January 11, 2018\n|}\n\n=== Spin-offs and Specials ===\n\n====Holiday Specials====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n!#\n!Episode\n!Published\n|-\n|1\n|The Legend of [[Krampus]]\n|December 17, 2017\n|-\n|2\n|Hey There Demons, It's A Spooky Yule Log\n|December 17, 2018\n|}\n\n==== Retrospectives ====\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n!#\n!Episode\n!Published\n|-\n|1\n|Unsolved Almost 70th Episode Retrospective\n|July 15, 2018\n|}\n\n==== Crossovers ====\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n!#\n!Episode\n!Published\n|-\n|1\n|[[The Try Guys]] Sleep In A Fan's Haunted Bedroom \u2022 The Try Vlog (feat. BuzzFeed Unsolved)\n|September 30, 2017\n|-\n|2\n|Ryan And Shane Make Each Other In [[The Sims 4]]\n|June 9, 2018\n|-\n|3\n|Ryan & Shane Choose A Fan's Haunted House \u2022 [[The Sims 4]]\n|June 26, 2018\n|-\n|4\n|Shane Controls His Friend's Life In [[The Sims 4]] \u2022 Ryan\n|August 4, 2018\n|-\n|5\n|Ryan And Shane Try To Make Apple Taters\n|August 5, 2018\n|-\n|6\n|We Styled Ryan & Shane \u2022 Ladylike\n|August 8, 2018\n|-\n|7\n|Ryan Control's His Friend's Life in [[The Sims 4]] \u2022 Shane\n|August 11, 2018\n|-\n|8\n|Ryan & Shane Seduce A Ghost In [[The Sims 4]]\n|August 18, 2018\n|-\n|9\n|Shane and Ryan Try To Kill [[The Try Guys]] In [[The Sims 4]] \n|August 25, 2018\n|-\n|10\n|[[Worth It (TV series)|Worth It]] Meets Unsolved In [[The Sims 4]]\n|November 17, 2018\n\n|}\n\n==The Hot Daga==\n{{Only primary sources|section|date=September 2019}}\nThe \"Hot Daga\" is an animated mini show series shown at the end of Postmortem episodes, created, written, and narrated by host Shane Madej. It's the bst story ever and should win an award. The first episode of the Hot Daga Saga began at the end of the Postmortem episode \"The Boy in the Box - Q+A\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dPfbqY4REL8 |title=The Boy In The Box - Q+A |author=BuzzFeed Multiplayer |via=YouTube}}</ref> Although at the beginning of episodes, Madej jokes that the show is commissioned by his co-host Ryan Bergara, Bergara is infamously not a fan of the series. However, Bergara listens to the show as it is narrated to the audience, though he does not fail to admonish it at any given opportunity.\n\nNotable characters include Pam, the evil hotdog witch, Gene, the french fries, Maizie, a holographic lesbian corn icon, and the Plupples (fruits that are like peaches, but sexier and blue). Another character, Dr. Ernesto Gordon Goondis, is voiced by Bergara through Madej's splicing of many of his dialogues from ''Unsolved'' and connecting them to create the voice of the character.\n\nThe series originated when Madej jokingly wanted a [[skateboarding]] [[hot dog]] at the end of a Q + A episode, and it has grown to multiple mini-episodes and musical numbers which are sung by Madej himself. Since Season 5 True Crime, the end of some Postmortem episodes have included a \"Roast Mortem\" section where the hosts go through commenters' roasts on the hosts in the episode in question. This segment has replaced the Hot Daga episodes.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|c=UCKijjvu6bN1c-ZHVwR7-5WA|Buzzfeed Unsolved Network}}\n*{{IMDb title|7194764|Buzzfeed Unsolved: True Crime}}\n*{{IMDb title|6723522|Buzzfeed Unsolved: Supernatural}}\n\n{{BuzzFeed}}\n\n[[Category:2016 web series debuts]]\n[[Category:American web series]]\n[[Category:Documentary web series]]\n[[Category:Mystery web series]]\n[[Category:YouTube series]]\n[[Category:BuzzFeed]]\n", "name_user": "Gharken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Hot Daga", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BuzzFeed_Unsolved"}
{"title_page": "Sankalp Reddy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sankalp Reddy\n| image        = Smriti Irani presenting the Rajat Kamal Award to Sankalp (Best Telgu Film) for the Feature film \u2013 GHAZI, at the 65th National Film Awards Function, in New Delhi.JPG\n| caption      = Sankalp Reddy receiving the National Film Award.\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1984}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], [[India]]\n| occupation   = Director, writer\n| years_active = 2014 \u2013 present\n| spouse       = Keerthi Reddy\n| children     = 2 \n| awards       =\n| website      = \n| alma mater     = [[Griffith Film School]]\n}}\n'''Sankalp Reddy''' (born October 20, 1984) is an [[Indian film]] director, and screenwriter known for his works in [[Telugu cinema]], and [[bollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/tollywood/160818/varun-tej-looks-out-of-this-world.html|title=Varun Tej looks out of this world}}</ref> He made his directorial debut with ''[[The Ghazi Attack]]'' \ninspired by true events from the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/tollywood/170517/director-sankalp-reddy-to-do-a-science-fiction-film.html|title=Director Sankalp Reddy to do a science fiction film|date=17 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/The-making-of-a-war-story/article17320239.ece|title=The making of a war story|first=Nivedita|last=Ganguly|date=17 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> The submarine warfare film is an underwater tale of the courage and patriotism of the men aboard the Indian Submarine ''[[INS Karanj (S21)]]'' which destroyed the Pakistani ''[[PNS Ghazi]]'' when it ventured into Indian waters to destroy ''[[INS Vikrant]]'' on the shore of R. K. Beach, Visakhapatnam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151124/nation-current-affairs/article/visakhapatnam-sunk-pakistani-submarine-ghazi-enigma|title=Visakhapatnam: Sunk Pakistani submarine Ghazi is an enigma|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scoopwhoop.com/The-Real-Story-Of-The-Ghazi-Attack/|title=The Ghazi Attack: An Indo-Pak War So Deep Underwater That It Never Surfaced In History|first=|last=ScoopWhoop|date=11 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nGhazi, was screened at the [[Jagran Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insider.in/top-films-to-watch-at-jagran-film-festival/article|title=10 Films You Shouldn't Miss At The Jagran Film Festival|website=insider.in}}</ref> and has garnered the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] at the [[65th National Film Awards]] 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://164.100.117.97/WriteReadData/userfiles/65th%20%20NATIONAL%20FILM%20AWARDS%20FOR%202017-%20final%20(1).pdf|title=65th National Film Awards}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/65th-national-film-awards-live-sridevi-posthumously-awarded-best-actress-for-mom-newton-wins-best-hindi-film-1717053.html|title=65th National Film Awards LIVE: Sridevi Posthumously Awarded Best Actress; Vinod Khanna Honoured With Dada Saheb Phalke Award |publisher=News 18date=13 April 2018|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Sankalp directed the space thriller film [[Antariksham 9000 KMPH]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/antariksham-9000-kmph-teaser-a-promising-thrilling-space-adventure-on-the-cards/articleshow/66262523.cms|title=Antariksham 9000 KMPH Teaser: A promising & thrilling space-adventure on the cards}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in Hyderabad. His family hails from [[Ibrahimpatnam, Ranga Reddy district]], [[Telangana]]. He did his schooling in Hyderabad, engineering from [[CVR College of Engineering]] and graduated in 2006. He went to do pursue his MBA at [[Griffith University]], [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]], but dropped out after a semester and joined [[Griffith Film School]], a top [[creative arts]] school in Australia, for pursuing [[Masters of Fine Arts|MFA]] in film direction and completed it in 2009.<ref>http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141221/entertainment-tollywood/article/india\u2019s-first-submarine-warfare-movie-coming-hyderabad</ref>\n\n[[File:Sankalp Reddy.jpg|thumb|Sankalp Reddy in Cinivaram, Ravindra Bharathi, Hyderabad]]\n\n==Career==\nHe worked as a software engineer for 6 months at [[Infotech IT]] before going to Australia to pursue higher education.\n\nHe directed 4 short films before entering Tollywood. He even did a few short films on his [[iPhone]]. He started a [[Previsualization|Previz]] Company with the name Krystal 3C in Hyderabad which provided Previz service for his movie The Ghazi Attack.\n\n===Tollywood===\nHe wanted to develop a book into a film script, so he wrote a book, The Blue Fish and later turned into the foundation for the debut Telugu film, [[The Ghazi Attack]]. He hired a lot of actors from Sutradhaar theater group, Hyderabad for the movie.\n\nHis second film [[Antariksham 9000 KMPH]] has [[Varun Tej]] is lead actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/varun-tejs-space-thriller-antariksham-9000-kmph-wraps-up-its-shoot/articleshow/66029054.cms|title=Varun Tej\u2019s space-thriller Antariksham 9000 KMPH wraps up its shoot}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Writer/Dialogues\n! Screenplay\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[The Ghazi Attack]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Rana Daggubati\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Antariksham 9000 KMPH]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|[[Varun Tej]]  \n|-\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8623146/ imdb]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reddy, Sankalp}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telugu film directors]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Indian experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Casting directors]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Telangana]]\n[[Category:National Film Award (India) winners]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Telangana]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sankalp Reddy\n| image        = Smriti Irani presenting the Rajat Kamal Award to Sankalp (Best Telgu Film) for the Feature film \u2013 GHAZI, at the 65th National Film Awards Function, in New Delhi.JPG\n| caption      = Sankalp Reddy receiving the National Film Award.\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1984}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], [[India]]\n| occupation   = Director, writer\n| years_active = 2014 \u2013 present\n| spouse       = Keerthi Reddy\n| children     = 2 \n| awards       =\n| website      = \n| alma mater     = [[Griffith Film School]]\n}}\n'''Sankalp Reddy''' (born October 20, 1984) is an [[Indian film]] director, and screenwriter known for his works in [[Telugu cinema]], and [[bollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/tollywood/160818/varun-tej-looks-out-of-this-world.html|title=Varun Tej looks out of this world}}</ref> He made his directorial debut with ''[[The Ghazi Attack]]'' \ninspired by true events from the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/tollywood/170517/director-sankalp-reddy-to-do-a-science-fiction-film.html|title=Director Sankalp Reddy to do a science fiction film|date=17 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/The-making-of-a-war-story/article17320239.ece|title=The making of a war story|first=Nivedita|last=Ganguly|date=17 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> The submarine warfare film is an underwater tale of the courage and patriotism of the men aboard the Indian Submarine ''[[INS Karanj (S21)]]'' which destroyed the Pakistani ''[[PNS Ghazi]]'' when it ventured into Indian waters to destroy ''[[INS Vikrant]]'' on the shore of R. K. Beach, Visakhapatnam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151124/nation-current-affairs/article/visakhapatnam-sunk-pakistani-submarine-ghazi-enigma|title=Visakhapatnam: Sunk Pakistani submarine Ghazi is an enigma|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scoopwhoop.com/The-Real-Story-Of-The-Ghazi-Attack/|title=The Ghazi Attack: An Indo-Pak War So Deep Underwater That It Never Surfaced In History|first=|last=ScoopWhoop|date=11 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nGhazi, was screened at the [[Jagran Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insider.in/top-films-to-watch-at-jagran-film-festival/article|title=10 Films You Shouldn't Miss At The Jagran Film Festival|website=insider.in}}</ref> and has garnered the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] at the [[65th National Film Awards]] 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://164.100.117.97/WriteReadData/userfiles/65th%20%20NATIONAL%20FILM%20AWARDS%20FOR%202017-%20final%20(1).pdf|title=65th National Film Awards}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/65th-national-film-awards-live-sridevi-posthumously-awarded-best-actress-for-mom-newton-wins-best-hindi-film-1717053.html|title=65th National Film Awards LIVE: Sridevi Posthumously Awarded Best Actress; Vinod Khanna Honoured With Dada Saheb Phalke Award |publisher=News 18date=13 April 2018|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Sankalp directed the space thriller film [[Antariksham 9000 KMPH]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/antariksham-9000-kmph-teaser-a-promising-thrilling-space-adventure-on-the-cards/articleshow/66262523.cms|title=Antariksham 9000 KMPH Teaser: A promising & thrilling space-adventure on the cards}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in Hyderabad. His family hails from [[Ibrahimpatnam, Ranga Reddy district]], [[Telangana]]. He did his schooling in Hyderabad, engineering from [[CVR College of Engineering]] and graduated in 2006. He went to do pursue his MBA at [[Griffith University]], [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]], but dropped out after a semester and joined [[Griffith Film School]], a top [[creative arts]] school in Australia, for pursuing [[Masters of Fine Arts|MFA]] in film direction and completed it in 2009.<ref>http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141221/entertainment-tollywood/article/india\u2019s-first-submarine-warfare-movie-coming-hyderabad</ref>\n\n[[File:Sankalp Reddy.jpg|thumb|Sankalp Reddy in Cinivaram, Ravindra Bharathi, Hyderabad]]\n\n==Career==\nHe worked as a software engineer for 6 months at [[Infotech IT]] before going to Australia to pursue higher education.\n\nHe directed 4 short films before entering Tollywood. He even did a few short films on his [[iPhone]]. He started a [[Previsualization|Previz]] Company with the name Krystal 3C in Hyderabad which provided Previz service for his movie The Ghazi Attack.\n\n===Tollywood===\nHe wanted to develop a book into a film script, so he wrote a book, The Blue Fish and later turned into the foundation for the debut Telugu film, [[The Ghazi Attack]]. He hired a lot of actors from Sutradhaar theater group, Hyderabad for the movie.\n\nHis second film [[Antariksham 9000 KMPH]] has [[Varun Tej]] is lead actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/varun-tejs-space-thriller-antariksham-9000-kmph-wraps-up-its-shoot/articleshow/66029054.cms|title=Varun Tej\u2019s space-thriller Antariksham 9000 KMPH wraps up its shoot}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Writer/Dialogues\n! Screenplay\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[The Ghazi Attack]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}