{"title_page": "Emil Coppetti", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss bobsledder}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Emil Coppetti\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Swiss\n| sport          = [[Bobsleigh]]\n| birth_date     = 1902\n| birth_place    = [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Emil Coppetti''' (born 1902, date of death unknown) was a Swiss [[Bobsleigh|bobsledder]]. He competed in the [[Bobsleigh at the 1928 Winter Olympics|four-man event]] at the [[1928 Winter Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/co/emil-coppetti-1.html |title=Emil Coppetti Olympic Results |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coppetti, Emil}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Swiss male bobsledders]]\n[[Category:Olympic bobsledders of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Bobsledders at the 1928 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Z\u00fcrich]]\n{{Switzerland-bobsleigh-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss bobsledder}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Emil Coppetti\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Swiss\n| sport          = [[Bobsleigh]]\n| birth_date     = 1902\n| birth_place    = [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Emil Coppetti''' (born 1902, date of death unknown) was a Swiss [[Bobsleigh|bobsledder]]. He competed in the [[Bobsleigh at the 1928 Winter Olympics|four-man event]] at the [[1928 Winter Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/co/emil-coppetti-1.html |title=Emil Coppetti Olympic Results |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coppetti, Emil}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Swiss male bobsledders]]\n[[Category:Olympic bobsledders of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Bobsledders at the 1928 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Z\u00fcrich]]\n{{Switzerland-bobsleigh-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_Coppetti"}
{"title_page": "Trinity High School (Washington, Pennsylvania)", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Trinity High School\n|image          = Trinity High School (Washington, Pennsylvania).jpg\n|motto          =\n|established    =\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|affiliation    =\n|district       = [[Trinity Area School District]]\n|grades         = 9\u201312\n|principal      = Thomas J. Samosky\n|faculty        =\n|staff          =\n|students       =\n|enrollment     =\n|athletics      =\n|conference     =\n|colors         =Blue&White\n|mascot         = Hiller\n|location       = 231 Park Avenue\n|city           = [[Washington, Pennsylvania]]\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|40.16472|N|80.24944|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|zipcode        = 15301\n|country        = United States\n|website        = {{url|1=https://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/1/home}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| embed = yes\n| name =Trinity Hall\n| nrhp_type =\n  | designated_other1_name = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation Landmark\n  | designated_other1_date = \n  | designated_other1_link = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation\n  | designated_other1_color = #f5dc0f\n| image =\n| caption =\n| nearest_city= [[Washington, Pennsylvania]]\n| area =\n| built =1857\n| architect= Copeland, T.V.; [[McKim, Mead, and White]]\n| architecture= Italianate\n| added = September 27, 1976\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum=76001681 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}} }}\n'''Trinity High School''' is a [[public high school]] on a hilltop overlooking [[Washington, Pennsylvania]], United States. Its bell tower has been a landmark in [[Washington County, Pennsylvania|Washington County]] for over a century.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt is designated as a historic public landmark by the [[Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web| title = Trinity Hall| work = Landmark Registry \u2013 Public Landmark| publisher = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation| year = 2008| url = http://www.washcolandmarks.com/landmark_registry_display.php| accessdate = 2010-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title =Trinity Hall|work = Spotlight Buildings| publisher = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation| year = 2008| url =http://www.washcolandmarks.com/trinity_hall.html| accessdate =2010-11-09|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5u75JAKGU |archivedate=2010-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Spring Hill===\nThe historic section of the school was once Trinity Hall School for Boys that operated from 1879 to 1906. The historic school grounds in North Franklin Township date back to the 1850s when Joseph McKnight built a home on top of a hill overlooking the then-borough of [[Washington, Pennsylvania]].  This twenty-five room Italianate mansion called Spring Hill now functions as the district's administrative offices connected to Trinity High School.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=250 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\nSpring Hill was purchased by William Smith, a prominent Washington dry goods merchant, as the new home for his son. The Smith family hired Boston-based landscape artist [[Robert Morris Copeland]] to prepare the grounds along Catfish Creek before it was occupied by William Wrenshaw Smith and his wife Emma Willard McKennan Smith. Wrenshaw Smith was a cousin to [[Julia Dent]], wife of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]. Wrenshaw Smith also served as Grant's aide-de-camp during the Civil War and Grant visited the Spring Hill mansion on multiple occasions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=250, 271 n. 13 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chernow |first1=Rob |title=Grant |date=2017 |publisher=Penguin Press |location=New York |page=838}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity Hall School for Boys===\nWilliam Wrenshaw Smith was a devout [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]] and longtime vestryman at Trinity Episcopal Church, then located on Beau Street near Washington and Jefferson College. During the 1860s, Smith worked alongside [[John Barrett Kerfoot]], newly elected [[Episcopal Diocese of Pittsburgh|Bishop of Pittsburgh]], to create a boys\u2019 school following the curricular model of famed priest-educator [[William Augustus Muhlenberg]].  In this model, \u201cthe school was to be like a large family with a priest as rector serving as father-figure ''in loco parentis''.\u201d Trinity Hall operated from 1870 to 1906 attracting members of prominent regional families including Heinz, Carnegie, Kammerer, and LeMoyne along with a grandson of President Grant.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=257, 262\u2013263, 278 n. 99 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\nIn 1883, Trinity School for Boys began adopting elements of [[Muscular Christianity]]. This included a \u201cmilitary department\u201d for purposes of exercise and a more generic Protestant Christianity in place of Muhlenberg's strictly Episcopalian church school model. Sometimes this leads to overemphasis on the military nature of the school and mistaken conclusions that Trinity Hall was a strict military academy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=259 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref><ref name=PostGazette>Crompton, Janice. [http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB48EADCF36CC6D&p_docnum=8&p_queryname=NaN&p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated4&p_nbid=G56N5DJUMTE4NTg0NzQ0OS4yODY4NjU6MTo3OnJhLTE4ODg \"SUPERINTENDENT PUSHES FOR TRINITY HALL RESTORATION\"], ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', November 29, 1998. Accessed July 31, 2007.</ref> Various Episcopal priests served as school [[Rector (academia)|rector]] until the 1890s when patron William Wrenshaw Smith became lay rector, a change possibly due to declining enrollment and revenue. Trinity Hall closed in 1906, two years after Smith's death.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=260, 265\u2013266 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity Hall becomes Trinity High===\nTrinity Hall, a Smith family property, stood vacant for nearly two decades. In 1922, it was unsuccessfully considered as a site for relocating [[Presbyterian]]-affiliated [[Washington Female Seminary]]. Then in 1925 the townships of [[Amwell Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|Amwell]], [[Canton Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|Canton]], [[North Franklin Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|North Franklin]], and [[South Strabane Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|South Strabane]] purchased the Trinity Hall property to repurpose as a joint public high school. The sale nearly fell through. Amwell Township's secretary refused to sign documents until forced to do so by the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |pages=268, 277 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref> The classroom block of Trinity Hall was used from 1883 until 2004. It was demolished in 2006. The Spring Hill section of Trinity Hall continues to serve as offices for Trinity Area School District.\n\nToday, Trinity is a modern public school housing approximately 1,279 students in grades 9\u201312 on a campus-style setting.<ref>[http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&InstName=trinity&State=42&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&ID=422376006012 Data for Trinity High School], National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed July 31, 2007.</ref> Trinity Area School District maintains a small Trinity Hall Museum open by appointment only.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petsko |first1=Emily |title=Trinity to preserve history of military academy |url=https://observer-reporter.com/news/localnews/trinity-to-preserve-history-of-military-academy/article_a781d774-a38e-575a-88b7-189401922454.html |work=Observer-Reporter |date=March 17, 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trinitypride.org/about/trinity-hall-museum|title=Trinity Schools - Trinity Hall Museum|last=Coyle|first=Ryan|website=www.trinitypride.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Academics program==\nTrinity High School offers 13 Advanced Placement classes and two languages.  Spanish and German. These language courses include classes from level one to level five honors. There are elective and core subjects in the areas of arts, music, business, English, science, history, mathematics, social studies, and journalism.\n\n==Graduation rate==\nIn 2011, the [[Pennsylvania Department of Education]] issued a new, 4 year cohort graduation rate. Trinity School District's graduation rate was calculated to be 85% for 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.education.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt/community/pennsylvania_department_of_education/7237/info/757639 |title=New 4-year Cohort Graduation Rate Calculation Now Being Implemented |author=Pennsylvania Department of Education |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Academic achievement==\nIn 2011, Trinity Senior High School declined to 'Warning' AYP status due to lagging mathematics achievement. The math achievement fell below the State AYP goal of 67% for Math and below the statewide 11th grade achievement level of 60% on grade level. In 2010, the school achieved '''AYP''' status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://paayp.emetric.net/School/Overview/c63/101638003/6012 |title=Trinity Senior High School AYP Overview |author=Pennsylvania Department of Education |date=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the 11th grade ranked 40th among 122 western Pennsylvania school district 11th grades, for academic achievement as measured by five years of the PSSAs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/events/pennsylvania_schools/schooldetails.html?DistrictNumber=101638003&SchoolNumber=6638 |title=School And School District Information 2011 Guide to Western Pennsylvania Schools |author=Pittsburgh Business Times |date=April 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Graduation requirements==\nThe Trinity Area School District School Board has determined that students must earn 22 credits to graduate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.org/files/43274/Student%20Handbook%202009_2010.pdf |title=Trinity Area School District Student Handbook |author=Trinity Area School District Administration}}</ref>\n\nBy law, all Pennsylvania secondary school students must complete a project as a part of their eligibility to graduate from high school. The type of project, its rigor and its expectations are set by the individual school district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacode.com/secure/data/022/chapter4/s4.24.html |title=Pennsylvania Code \u00a74.24 (a) High school graduation requirements}}</ref> At Trinity High School the graduation project includes: community service, school visitation, job shadowing and a written paper.\n\n== Activities and athletics ==\nTrinity High School offers a wide variety of extracurricular activities and sports.  Football, baseball, basketball, soccer, cross-country, track, wrestling, volleyball, golf, rifle, lacrosse, ice hockey, swimming, softball, tennis, and cheerleading are available at Trinity.  They are in the WPIAL AAA and AAAA divisions for their sports.  The [[ice hockey]]<ref>[http://www.trinityhillers.com PIHL | Trinity Ice Hockey Club]</ref> teams compete in the PIHL Open Division.\n\nEligibility to participate in all extracurriculars and athletics is set by Trinity School Board policies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/documents.cfm?id=405&master=40713&located=1 |title=Extracurricular Activities Policy 122 |author=Trinity Area School Board}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/documents.cfm?id=405&master=40713&located=1 |title=Interscholastic Athletics Policy 123 |author=Trinity Area School Board}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, an investigation was conducted into the uncontrolled spending of the Trinity High School athletics coaches. The report called for various changes to assure appropriate, student focused, spending.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.observer-reporter.com/www/PDF/trinityathletic.pdf |title=Athletic Department Investigation Trinity Area School District |date=April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Abraham Higginbotham]], actor, comedian, and TV producer\n* [[Jesse William Lazear]], yellow fever researcher\n* [[Joseph Albert Walker]], American astronaut and test pilot\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[{{NRHP-PA|H001174_01H.pdf}} National Register nomination form]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation}}\n{{Washington, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:McKim, Mead & White buildings]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1857]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Schools in Washington County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Washington County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Trinity High School\n|image          = Trinity High School (Washington, Pennsylvania).jpg\n|motto          =\n|established    =\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|affiliation    =\n|district       = [[Trinity Area School District]]\n|grades         = 9\u201312\n|principal      = Thomas J. Samosky\n|faculty        =\n|staff          =\n|students       =\n|enrollment     =\n|athletics      =\n|conference     =\n|colors         =Blue&White\n|mascot         = Hiller\n|location       = 231 Park Avenue\n|city           = [[Washington, Pennsylvania]]\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|40.16472|N|80.24944|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|zipcode        = 15301\n|country        = United States\n|website        = {{url|1=https://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/1/home}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| embed = yes\n| name =Trinity Hall\n| nrhp_type =\n  | designated_other1_name = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation Landmark\n  | designated_other1_date = \n  | designated_other1_link = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation\n  | designated_other1_color = #f5dc0f\n| image =\n| caption =\n| nearest_city= [[Washington, Pennsylvania]]\n| area =\n| built =1857\n| architect= Copeland, T.V.; [[McKim, Mead, and White]]\n| architecture= Italianate\n| added = September 27, 1976\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum=76001681 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}} }}\n'''Trinity High School''' is a [[public high school]] located on a hilltop overlooking the city of [[Washington, Pennsylvania]], United States. Its bell tower has been a landmark in [[Washington County, Pennsylvania|Washington County]] for over a century.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt is designated as a historic public landmark by the [[Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web| title = Trinity Hall| work = Landmark Registry \u2013 Public Landmark| publisher = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation| year = 2008| url = http://www.washcolandmarks.com/landmark_registry_display.php| accessdate = 2010-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title =Trinity Hall|work = Spotlight Buildings| publisher = Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation| year = 2008| url =http://www.washcolandmarks.com/trinity_hall.html| accessdate =2010-11-09|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5u75JAKGU |archivedate=2010-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Spring Hill===\nThe historic section of the school was once Trinity Hall School for Boys that operated from 1879 to 1906. The historic school grounds in North Franklin Township date back to the 1850s when Joseph McKnight built a home on top of a hill overlooking the then-borough of [[Washington, Pennsylvania]].  This twenty-five room Italianate mansion called Spring Hill now functions as the district\u2019s administrative offices connected to Trinity High School.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=250 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\nSpring Hill was purchased by William Smith, a prominent Washington dry goods merchant, as the new home for his son. The Smith family hired Boston-based landscape artist [[Robert Morris Copeland]] to prepare the grounds along Catfish Creek before it was occupied by William Wrenshaw Smith and his wife Emma Willard McKennan Smith. Wrenshaw Smith was a cousin to [[Julia Dent]], wife of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]. Wrenshaw Smith also served as Grant's aide-de-camp during the Civil War and Grant visited the Spring Hill mansion on multiple occassions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=250, 271 n. 13 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chernow |first1=Rob |title=Grant |date=2017 |publisher=Penguin Press |location=New York |page=838}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity Hall School for Boys===\nWilliam Wrenshaw Smith was a devout [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]] and longtime vestryman at Trinity Episcopal Church, then located on Beau Street near Washington and Jefferson College. During the 1860s, Smith worked alongside [[John Barrett Kerfoot|John Barrett Kerfoot]], newly elected [[Episcopal Diocese of Pittsburgh|Bishop of Pittsburgh]], to create a boys\u2019 school following the curricular model of famed priest-educator [[William Augustus Muhlenberg]].  In this model, \u201cthe school was to be like a large family with a priest as rector serving as father-figure ''in loco parentis''.\u201d Trinity Hall operated from 1870 to 1906 attracting members of prominent regional families including Heinz, Carnegie, Kammerer, and LeMoyne along with a grandson of President Grant.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=257, 262-263, 278 n. 99 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\nIn 1883, Trinity School for Boys began adopting elements of [[Muscular Christianity]]. This included a \u201cmilitary department\u201d for purposes of exercise and a more generic Protestant Christianity in place of Muhlenberg\u2019s strictly Episcopalian church school model. Sometimes this leads to overemphasis on the military nature of the school and mistaken conclusions that Trinity Hall was a strict military academy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=259 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref><ref name=PostGazette>Crompton, Janice. [http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB48EADCF36CC6D&p_docnum=8&p_queryname=NaN&p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated4&p_nbid=G56N5DJUMTE4NTg0NzQ0OS4yODY4NjU6MTo3OnJhLTE4ODg \"SUPERINTENDENT PUSHES FOR TRINITY HALL RESTORATION\"], ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', November 29, 1998. Accessed July 31, 2007.</ref> Various Episcopal priests served as school [[Rector (academia)|rector]] until the 1890s when patron William Wrenshaw Smith became lay rector, a change possibly due to declining enrollment and revenue. Trinity Hall closed in 1906, two years after Smith\u2019s death.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=260, 265-266 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity Hall becomes Trinity High===\nTrinity Hall, a Smith family property, stood vacant for nearly two decades. In 1922, it was unsuccessfully considered as a site for relocating [[Presbyterian]]-affiliated [[Washington Female Seminary]]. Then in 1925 the townships of [[Amwell Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|Amwell]], [[Canton Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|Canton]], [[North Franklin Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|North Franklin]], and [[South Strabane Township, Washington County, Pennsylvania|South Strabane]] purchased the Trinity Hall property to repurpose as a joint public high school. The sale nearly fell through. Amwell Township\u2019s secretary refused to sign documents until forced to do so by the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richards |first1=Samuel J. |title=A Forgotten Muhlenberg School:  Trinity Hall in Washington, Pennsylvania |journal=Pennsylvania History:  A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies |date=2020 |volume=87 |issue=2 |page=268, 277 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/751947}}</ref> The classroom block of Trinity Hall was used from 1883 until 2004. It was demolished in 2006. The Spring Hill section of Trinity Hall continues to serve as offices for Trinity Area School District.\n\nToday, Trinity is a modern public school housing approximately 1,279 students in grades 9\u201312 on a campus-style setting.<ref>[http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&InstName=trinity&State=42&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&ID=422376006012 Data for Trinity High School], National Center for Education Statistics. Accessed July 31, 2007.</ref> Trinity Area School District maintains a small Trinity Hall Museum open by appointment only.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petsko |first1=Emily |title=Trinity to preserve history of military academy |url=https://observer-reporter.com/news/localnews/trinity-to-preserve-history-of-military-academy/article_a781d774-a38e-575a-88b7-189401922454.html |work=Observer-Reporter |date=March 17, 2015 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trinitypride.org/about/trinity-hall-museum|title=Trinity Schools - Trinity Hall Museum|last=Coyle|first=Ryan|website=www.trinitypride.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Academics program==\nTrinity High School offers 13 Advanced Placement classes and two languages.  Spanish and German. These language courses include classes from level one to level five honors. There are elective and core subjects in the areas of arts, music, business, English, science, history, mathematics, social studies, and journalism.\n\n==Graduation rate==\nIn 2011, the [[Pennsylvania Department of Education]] issued a new, 4 year cohort graduation rate. Trinity School District's graduation rate was calculated to be 85% for 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.education.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt/community/pennsylvania_department_of_education/7237/info/757639 |title=New 4-year Cohort Graduation Rate Calculation Now Being Implemented |author=Pennsylvania Department of Education |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Academic achievement==\nIn 2011, Trinity Senior High School declined to 'Warning' AYP status due to lagging mathematics achievement. The math achievement fell below the State AYP goal of 67% for Math and below the statewide 11th grade achievement level of 60% on grade level. In 2010, the school achieved '''AYP''' status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://paayp.emetric.net/School/Overview/c63/101638003/6012 |title=Trinity Senior High School AYP Overview |author=Pennsylvania Department of Education |date=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the 11th grade ranked 40th among 122 western Pennsylvania school district 11th grades, for academic achievement as measured by five years of the PSSAs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/events/pennsylvania_schools/schooldetails.html?DistrictNumber=101638003&SchoolNumber=6638 |title=School And School District Information 2011 Guide to Western Pennsylvania Schools |author=Pittsburgh Business Times |date=April 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Graduation requirements==\nThe Trinity Area School District School Board has determined that students must earn 22 credits to graduate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.org/files/43274/Student%20Handbook%202009_2010.pdf |title=Trinity Area School District Student Handbook |author=Trinity Area School District Administration}}</ref>\n\nBy law, all Pennsylvania secondary school students must complete a project as a part of their eligibility to graduate from high school. The type of project, its rigor and its expectations are set by the individual school district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacode.com/secure/data/022/chapter4/s4.24.html |title=Pennsylvania Code \u00a74.24 (a) High school graduation requirements}}</ref> At Trinity High School the graduation project includes: community service, school visitation, job shadowing and a written paper.\n\n== Activities and athletics ==\nTrinity High School offers a wide variety of extracurricular activities and sports.  Football, baseball, basketball, soccer, cross-country, track, wrestling, volleyball, golf, rifle, lacrosse, ice hockey, swimming, softball, tennis, and cheerleading are available at Trinity.  They are in the WPIAL AAA and AAAA divisions for their sports.  The [[ice hockey]]<ref>[http://www.trinityhillers.com PIHL | Trinity Ice Hockey Club]</ref> teams compete in the PIHL Open Division.\n\nEligibility to participate in all extracurriculars and athletics is set by Trinity School Board policies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/documents.cfm?id=405&master=40713&located=1 |title=Extracurricular Activities Policy 122 |author=Trinity Area School Board}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitypride.k12.pa.us/documents.cfm?id=405&master=40713&located=1 |title=Interscholastic Athletics Policy 123 |author=Trinity Area School Board}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, an investigation was conducted into  the uncontrolled spending of the Trinity High School athletics coaches. The report called for various changes to assure appropriate, student focused, spending.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.observer-reporter.com/www/PDF/trinityathletic.pdf |title=Athletic Department Investigation Trinity Area School District |date=April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Joseph Albert Walker]], American astronaut and test pilot\n*[[Abraham Higginbotham]], actor, comedian, and TV producer\n* [[Jesse William Lazear]], yellow fever researcher\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[{{NRHP-PA|H001174_01H.pdf}} National Register nomination form]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Washington County History & Landmarks Foundation}}\n{{Washington, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:McKim, Mead & White buildings]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1857]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Schools in Washington County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Washington County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: occassions \u2192 occasions, \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trinity_High_School_(Washington,_Pennsylvania)"}
{"title_page": "Gyraulus convexiusculus", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''\n| image =\n| image_caption = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' shell\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN 2014\">Van Damme, D. 2014. ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2014: e.T166681A42421590. https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2014-1.RLTS.T166681A42421590.en. Downloaded on 15 September 2018.</ref>\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia = clade [[Heterobranchia]]<br/>clade [[Euthyneura]]<br/>clade [[Panpulmonata]]<br/>clade [[Hygrophila (Gastropoda)|Hygrophila]]\n| superfamilia = [[Planorboidea]]\n| familia = [[Planorbidae]]\n| subfamilia = [[Planorbinae]]\n| tribus = [[Planorbini]]\n| genus = ''[[Gyraulus]]''\n| species = '''''G. convexiusculus'''''\n| binomial = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Thomas Hutton (zoologist)|Hutton]], 1849)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN 2014\"/>\n| synonyms =\n''Planorbis convexiusculus'' Hutton, 1849\n}}\n\n'''''Gyraulus convexiusculus''''' is a [[species]] of [[freshwater snail]], an [[Aquatic animal|aquatic]] [[pulmonate]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the family [[Planorbidae]], the [[sheep|ram]]'s horn snails.\n\n==Distribution==\nDistribution of ''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' includes [[Sistan and Baluchestan Province]] and [[Yazd Province]] in [[List of non-marine molluscs of Iran|Iran]],<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gl\u00f6er | first1 = P. | authorlink2 = Vladimir Pe\u0161i\u0107 | last2 = Pe\u0161i\u0107 | first2 = V. | year = 2012 | title = The freshwater snails (Gastropoda) of Iran, with descriptions of two new genera and eight new species | url = | journal = [[ZooKeys]] | volume = 219 | issue = | pages = 11\u201361 | doi = 10.3897/zookeys.219.3406 }}</ref> Afghanistan,<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\"/> Thailand,<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\"/> [[List of non-marine molluscs of Nepal|Nepal]],<ref name=\"Surana 2004\">{{cite journal | last1 = Surana | first1 = R. | last2 = Subba | first2 = B. R. | last3 = Limbu | first3 = K. P. | year = 2004 | title = Report of Molluscs from Chimdi lake (Birju Tal), Sunsari district, Eastern Nepal | url = | journal = Our Nature | volume = 2 | issue = | page = 1 | doi = 10.3126/on.v2i1.325 }}</ref> [[List of non-marine molluscs of South Korea|South Korea]],<ref name=\"Noseworthy 2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = Noseworthy | first1 = R. G. | last2 = Lim | first2 = N.-R. | last3 = Choi | first3 = K.-S. | year = 2007 | title = A Catalogue of the Mollusks of [[Jeju Island]], South Korea | url = https://www.academia.edu/7570561/A_Catalogue_of_the_Mollusks_of_Jeju_Island_South_Korea | journal = [[Korean Journal of Malacology]] | volume = 23 | issue = 1| pages = 65\u2013104 }}</ref> [[List of non-marine molluscs of Vietnam|Vietnam]].<ref name=\"Dung 2010\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dung | first1 = B. T. | last2 = Madsen | first2 = H. | last3 = The | first3 = D. T. | year = 2010 | title = Distribution of freshwater snails in family-based VAC ponds and associated waterbodies with special reference to intermediate hosts of fish-borne zoonotic trematodes in Nam Dinh Province, Vietnam | url = | journal = [[Acta Tropica]] | volume = 116 | issue = 1| pages = 15\u201323 | doi = 10.1016/j.actatropica.2010.04.016 | pmid = 20457118 }}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nPredators of include larvae of ''[[Luciola substriata]]''.<ref name=\"Fu et al.\">{{cite journal|last1=Fu|first1=Xinhua|last2=Ohba|first2=Nobuyoshi|last3=Vencl|first3=Fredric V.|last4=Lei|first4=Chaoliang|title=Structure, behavior, and the life cycle of an aquatic firefly, ''Luciola substriata'', in China|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/250370642|journal=The Canadian Entomologist|date=2005|volume=137|pages=83\u201390|doi=10.4039/N04-022}}</ref>\n\n''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' is the known first intermediate host of ''[[Artyfechinostomum malayanum]]''.<ref name=\"Chai 2009\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Chai | first1 = J. Y. | last2 = Shin | first2 = E. H. | last3 = Lee | first3 = S. H. | last4 = Rim | first4 = H. J. | title = Foodborne Intestinal Flukes in Southeast Asia | doi = 10.3347/kjp.2009.47.S.S69 | journal = The Korean Journal of Parasitology | volume = 47 | issue = Supplement | pages = S69\u2013102 | year = 2009 | pmid =  19885337| pmc =2769220 }}</ref>\n\n''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' is a potential first and second intermediate host of ''[[Echinostoma cinetorchis]]'' in Korea, based on laboratory work.<ref name=\"Chung 2001\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Chung | first1 = P. R. | last2 = Jung | first2 = Y. | last3 = Park | first3 = Y. K. | title = ''Segmentina hemisphaerula'': A New Molluscan Intermediate Host for ''Echinostoma cinetorchis'' in Korea | journal = Journal of Parasitology | volume = 87 | issue = 5 | pages = 1169\u20131171 | year = 2001 | doi = 10.1645/0022-3395(2001)087[1169:SHANMI]2.0.CO;2 | pmid =  11695387| pmc = }}</ref>\n\n==Human use==\nIt is a part of ornamental [[pet trade]] for [[Freshwater aquarium|freshwater aquaria]].<ref name=\"Ng 2016\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ng | first1 = T. H. | last2 = Tan | first2 = S. K. | last3 = Wong | first3 = W. H. | last4 = Meier | first4 = R. | last5 = Chan | first5 = S. Y. | last6 = Tan | first6 = H. H. | last7 = Yeo | first7 = D. C. | year = 2016 | title = Molluscs for sale: assessment of freshwater gastropods and bivalves in the ornamental pet trade | url = | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 11 | issue = 8| page = e0161130 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0161130 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q13649592}}\n\n[[Category:Gyraulus]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1849]]\n\n\n{{Planorbidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''\n| image =\n| image_caption = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' shell\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN 2014\">Van Damme, D. 2014. ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2014: e.T166681A42421590. https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2014-1.RLTS.T166681A42421590.en. Downloaded on 15 September 2018.</ref>\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia = clade [[Heterobranchia]]<br/>clade [[Euthyneura]]<br/>clade [[Panpulmonata]]<br/>clade [[Hygrophila (Gastropoda)|Hygrophila]]\n| superfamilia = [[Planorboidea]]\n| familia = [[Planorbidae]]\n| subfamilia = [[Planorbinae]]\n| tribus = [[Planorbini]]\n| genus = ''[[Gyraulus]]''\n| species = '''''G. convexiusculus'''''\n| binomial = ''Gyraulus convexiusculus''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Thomas Hutton (zoologist)|Hutton]], 1849)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN 2014\"/>\n| synonyms =\n''Planorbis convexiusculus'' Hutton, 1849\n}}\n\n'''''Gyraulus convexiusculus''''' is a [[species]] of [[freshwater snail]], an [[Aquatic animal|aquatic]] [[pulmonate]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the family [[Planorbidae]], the [[sheep|ram]]'s horn snails.\n\n==Distribution==\nDistribution of ''Gyraulus convexiusculus'' includes [[Sistan and Baluchestan Province]] and [[Yazd Province]] in [[List of non-marine molluscs of Iran|Iran]],<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\">Gl\u00f6er P. & [[Vladimir Pe\u0161i\u0107|Pe\u0161i\u0107 V.]] (2012). \"The freshwater snails (Gastropoda) of Iran, with descriptions of two new genera and eight new species\". ''[[ZooKeys]]'' '''219''': 11-61, {{doi|10.3897/zookeys.219.3406}}.</ref> Afghanistan,<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\"/> Thailand,<ref name=\"Gl\u00f6er 2012\"/> [[List of non-marine molluscs of Nepal|Nepal]],<ref name=\"Surana 2004\">Surana R., Subba B. R. & Limbu K. P. (2004). \"Report of Molluscs from Chimdi lake (Birju Tal), Sunsari district, Eastern Nepal\". ''Our Nature'' '''2'''(1). {{doi|10.3126/on.v2i1.325}}.</ref> [[List of non-marine molluscs of South Korea|South Korea]],<ref name=\"Noseworthy 2007\"